Thankfully for the Redskins, the Packers ruined themselves with drops and penalties. Smith is off to a highly Smith-ian start so far this season but has an attackable Week 5 matchup in the Saints.
report: Alex Smith completed 12-of-20 passes for 220 yards, two touchdowns and an interception in the Redskins' 31-17, Week 3 win over the Packers.

impact: He added a four-yard rushing score, but Smith was far worse than his pedestrian numbers even suggest.  He did some stat-padding late in the blowout loss.  Smith threw multiple hospital balls to his targets in the pass game, getting both Adrian Peterson (knee) and Chris Thompson (ribs) injured, while also spiking numerous passes into the turf well short of his receivers.  Smith lost a hilariously-bad fumble that went about 20 feet into the air and backwards for an easy scoop for the Saints.  It's hard to believe how terrible the Redskins were coming out of their bye.  They're now on a short week ahead of a home game against Carolina.  Smith won't be a fantasy option.
report: Alex Smith completed 23-of-39 passes for 275 yards, no touchdowns, and one interception in the Redskins' 43-19, Week 5 loss to the Saints.

impact: He added five carries for 14 yards. Averaging an inexcusable 4.53 yards per attempt, Smith was mostly dreadful, but the Panthers could never make him pay by creating a turnover. The Redskins won on the back of their running game. Vernon Davis was schemed completely wide open on Smith's first score, though his second was a nice throw to Paul Richardson in the back of the end zone. With seven total touchdowns through five games, Smith will be a last-gasp QB2 against the Cowboys in Week 7.
report: Alex Smith completed 21-of-36 passes for 163 yards and two touchdowns in the Redskins' 23-17, Week 6 win over the Panthers.

impact: In vintage Smith fashion, his only score on the day came on a 23-yard screen pass to change-of-pace back Kapri Bibbs. No receiver topped 43 yards for Washington. Dallas' secondary admittedly presents a tough matchup, but it is the second straight week Smith's failed to exceed 175 passing yards. Given the club's run-first grind-it-out style of play, Smith should only be used in terrific matchups on paper -- like the one the Redskins face in Week 8 against the Giants.
report: Alex Smith completed 14-of-25 passes for 178 yards and one touchdown in Washington's Week 7 win over the Cowboys.

impact: Nelson caught a 23-yard pass on the second offensive play of the game then all but disappeared afterwards. He has now posted 35 receiving yards or less in 11 consecutive games dating back to last season. Nelson is not a starting option Week 3 versus the Dolphins.
report: Jordy Nelson caught 2-of-4 targets for 30 yards in Sunday's Week 2 loss to the Broncos.

impact: Nelson more than tripled his season yardage total. He went 2/73/1 on the Raiders' opening drive, capping it off by getting completely free in the end zone for a 12-yard score. 139 of Nelson's yards came in the first six minutes. He was obviously much quieter thereafter, but it was more than enough to keep Nelson on the fantasy radar. With the Raiders rotating big receiver days, Nelson will be a WR3/4 for Week 4 against the Browns.
report: Jordy Nelson caught 6-of-8 targets for 173 yards and a touchdown in the Raiders' Week 3 loss to the Dolphins.

impact: Nelson has turned it up since the Raiders moved him to slot receiver two games ago, shredding Cleveland and Miami for a combined 11/221/2 stat line.  He tacked on a pair of two-point conversions in Sunday's overtime win.  Nelson has earned WR3/flex treatment entering a Week 5 date with the Chargers.
report: Jordy Nelson has caught 5-of-8 targets for 48 yards and a touchdown in the Raiders' Week 4 win over the Browns.

impact: This was a very disappointing outcome in a game where Amari Cooper (concussion) and Seth Roberts (concussion) both went down.  Derek Carr refused to pull the trigger on difficult throws, however, and Seattle's pass rush dominated Oakland's beat-up offensive line.  Nelson will emerge from the Raiders' Week 7 bye as a shaky WR3/flex option.
report: Jordy Nelson caught 2-of-3 targets for six yards in Week 6 versus Seattle.

impact: After losing Amari Cooper (concussion), the Raiders are down to Jordy Nelson, Martavis Bryant, and Dwayne Harris at wide receiver.  Roberts immediately went to the locker room after suffering his fourth-quarter brain injury.  The slot receiver had five catches for 31 yards on six targets before departing.
report: Raiders WR Seth Roberts left Sunday's Week 6 game with a concussion.

impact: Dalvin Cook played every snap of the first two series before Murray opened the third series and then handled much of the clock-killing work in the fourth quarter.  Neither back found the end zone, while Murray wasn't targeted in the pass game.  Murray is little more than a handcuff to Cook owners.
report: Latavius Murray rushed 11 times for 42 yards in the Vikings' Week 1 win over the 49ers.

impact: Murray was stuck on two carries before Dalvin Cook left with a hamstring injury in overtime. That issue is reportedly minor -- Cook described it as a cramp -- but it is enough to keep Murray on fantasy rosters for now. That said, he is nothing more than a handcuff.
report: Latavius Murray rushed four times for 19 yards in the Vikings' Week 2 tie with the Packers.

impact: Oof. What initially appeared to be the perfect game script situation for Murray turned out to be an absolute nightmare for the Vikings' offense. Minnesota's offensive line was a travesty throughout the afternoon, allowing Kirk Cousins to be blindsided and fumble on the team's first two offensive possessions. By the time the Vikings got the ball back for their third possession, they were already staring down the barrel of a 17-0 deficit. Minnesota's backfield received a paltry four carries on the day, totaling 12 rushing yards (3.0 YPC). Murray's five catches fortunately salvaged what could've been an even bigger disaster of an outing. Dalvin Cook is expected to return on Thursday against the Rams.
report: Latavius Murray rushed two times for one yard and added five catches for 30 receiving yards in the Vikings' Week 3 loss to the Bills.

impact: It was yet another disappointing affair for a player who is now averaging 3.53 yards per carry. Ominously, Murray ceded both a red zone target and goal line carry to "Roc Thomas." If Dalvin Cook (hamstring) can ever get healthy, Murray might have a hard time carving out a role. For now, Cook seems unlikely to play in Week 6, leaving Murray in the desperation FLEX mix against the Cardinals.
report: Latavius Murray rushed 11 times for 42 yards in the Vikings' Week 5 win over the Eagles, adding two receptions for 14 additional yards.

impact: With Dalvin Cook out, Murray rebounded from his disappointing Week 5. He ripped the Cardinals for three 20-plus yard runs, with his touchdown coming on a highlight 21-yarder where he stiff-armed into the end-zone. Murray came into Sunday averaging just 3.5 YPC, but he made a case for a role when Dalvin Cook returns. Cook would be a plug-and-play RB2 if Cook isn't back for Week 7.
report: Latavius Murray rushed 24 times for 155 yards and a touchdown in the Vikings' Week 6 win over the Cardinals.

impact: He added two catches for 14 yards on a pair of targets.  Murray's first score was an 11-yard scamper up the middle, and the second was an untouched run through the left side from 38 yards away.  With Dalvin Cook still struggling to get healthy, Murray has emerged as a strong RB2 with reliable workloads.  If Cook sits again, Murray will again be in play Week 8 against the Saints.
report: Latavius Murray rushed 15 times for 69 yards and two touchdowns in the Vikings' Week 7 win over the Jets.

impact: Conner had one blip on his resume with a fumble in the 4th quarter that let the Browns back in the game, but other than that, had a dominant game as a dual purpose back. Conner had an untouched 4-yard rushing score in the 2nd quarter and then a 22-yard touchdown run in the 3rd quarter. On top of his performance, no other Steeler RB even registered a touch in the game. As long as Le'Veon Bell continues his hold out, Conner is a RB1 for fantasy purposes.
report: Steelers RB James Conner rushed 31 times for 135 yards and two touchdowns while catching 5-of-6 targets for 57 yards in Sunday's Week 1 game versus the Browns.

impact: With the Steelers down 21-0 by the end of the first quarter, they never bothered to establish the run. Conner missed some time with an injury, but the Steelers never announced what was bothering him. Stevan Ridley ran in his place. Conner was on the field to finish the game. Provided Le'Veon Bell does not report this week, Conner will again be a usage-based RB1 for Week 3 against the Bucs.
report: James Conner rushed eight times for 17 yards and a touchdown in the Steelers' Week 2 loss to the Chiefs, adding five receptions for 48 additional yards.

impact: Conner fell victim to gameflow with the Ravens winning time of possesion. The Steelers went pass-heavy after getting behind early and didn't have any red-zone trips. Conner managed to catch a two-point conversion to save his night, but it was still his worst game to date. Conner will be an RB2 for Week 5 against the Falcons.
report: James Conner rushed nine times for 19 yards and caught 3-of-7 targets for 25 yards in Week 4 against the Ravens.

impact: Conner touched the ball seven times for 72 yards and a score on the opening drive and never looked back. He was piling on yards after first contact against the Falcons' injury-ruined defense. Conner has now hit 185 yards from scrimmage in 2-of-5 games, though he's totaled just 204 yards across his other three contests. Thankfully for his fantasy owners, the Bengals are an attackable Week 6 matchup. The Steelers then go on bye in Week 7. That is when Le'Veon Bell is expected to finally return.
report: James Conner rushed 21 times for 110 yards and two touchdowns in the Steelers' Week 5 win over the Falcons, adding four receptions for 75 additional yards.

impact: He added four catches for 18 yards on seven targets.  The NFL's leading tackle-shedder, Conner showed it in this one, consistently bulldozing would-be tacklers and injuring a couple along the way as S Shawn Williams was concussed on one of the long runs.  Conner's scores were both of the one-yard plunge variety.  He should have had a third touchdown but was ruled down at the one before getting stuffed on 1st- and 3rd-and-goal runs.  A premier RB1, Conner's workload will now be subject to question with Le'Veon Bell expected to report to the team during the Week 7 bye.
report: James Conner rushed 19 times for 111 yards and two touchdowns in the Steelers' 28-21, Week 6 win over the Bengals.

impact: Jones was a healthy scratch the first three weeks. With Peyton Barber struggling, he'll be thrown into Tampa's backfield mix.  Jones had a rough preseason, but there's not much in his way for touches.
report: Bucs rookie RB Ronald Jones is expected to be active for Week 4.

impact: It was the rookie's regular season debut. With Tampa Bay trailing 38-3 at the half, Jones and teammate Peyton Barber never stood a chance on the ground. One positive takeaway is that Jones out-touched Barber 11-8 and led the Buccaneers in rushing yards (29). He'll likely be the first man up when the Bucs return from their Week 5 bye.
report: Ronald Jones handled 10 carries for 29 yards in the Bucs' Week 4 loss to the Bears.

impact: There was some hope Jones would emerge from the bye with a bigger role, but that did not happen. Peyton Barber both started and worked as the clear lead back. Jones appeared to be the back of choice in passing situations throughout the game, but Barber was in late and ended up with a receiving score. Jones is just a bench stash at this point.
report: Ronald Jones rushed once for three yards and hauled in all three of his targets for 16 yards in the Bucs' Week 6 loss to the Falcons.

impact: Jones was hardly used until Peyton Barber appeared to suffer an injury in the third quarter. After that, he tallied five of his six touches in the game, including a 2-yard rushing score set up by a long O.J. Howard reception. Jones may get an uptick if Barber is indeed injured heading into Week 8, but he is only a FLEX option at best when the Bucs head to Cincinnati.
report: Ronald Jones rushed six times for 13 yards and a touchdown while catching his lone target for 15 yards in Sunday's Week 7 win over the Browns.

impact: He wasn’t targeted in the passing game. Barber impressed in the first half, tallying 50 yards on eight carries before the break. His longest run of the afternoon came on a 23-yard burst with just over four minutes remaining in the first quarter. Tampa Bay built a big lead and tried to salt the clock by feeding it to Barber, though that approach mostly backfired as the Saints limited him to just 19 yards on 11 second-half carries (1.72 yards per attempt). Barber out-touched backup Jacquizz Rodgers by a commanding 19-3 margin in the victory while further establishing himself as the Bucs’ clear lead back. He’ll be a mere RB3 in a tough matchup with Philadelphia in Week 2.
report: Peyton Barber logged 69 yards on 19 carries Sunday in Tampa Bay’s Week 1 victory over the Saints.

impact: He has 91 yards on 35 carries this season; "good" for 2.6 yards per rush.  That isn't going to cut it for the Bucs' running game, making it imperative for them to give rookie Ronald Jones a longer look on the practice field this week.  Barber will remain a touchdown-or-bust flex option in Week 3 versus Pittsburgh.
report: Peyton Barber managed 22 yards on 16 carries and caught 1-of-2 targets for seven yards in the Bucs' Week 2 win over the Eagles.

impact: Second-round rookie Ronald Jones was also active, and promptly took his place at the table, out-touching Barber 11-8. Jones also led the Bucs in rushing yards (29) on an otherwise porous day from both. Tampa Bay will likely come out of their Week 5 bye with Jameis Winston and Ronald Jones as starters, seemingly making Barber droppable across all formats.
report: Peyton Barber rushed seven times for 24 yards in the Bucs' Week 4 loss to the Bears.

impact: There was some thought (hope) Ronald Jones would take on a bigger role coming out of the bye, but that did not materialize. Barber started and worked as the clear lead back. Jones seemed to be getting snaps in passing situations, but Barber was on the field late in the game and came down with a five-yard touchdown. Barber will face a tougher test next week against the Browns, but he will be a FLEX option.
report: Peyton Barber rushed 13 times for 82 yards and hauled in all four of his targets for 24 yards and a touchdown in the Bucs' Week 6 loss to the Falcons.

impact: Barber failed to secure either of his two targets in the passing game. He appeared to injure his ankle on his final target of the game in the third quarter and although the Bucs provided no update on his status in game, he never returned to the field the rest of the way. Barber's status will be one to monitor early in the week, but even if he is good to go in Week 8, he is at best a low-level FLEX option on the road against the Bengals.
report: Peyton Barber rushed 11 times for 30 yards in Sunday's Week 7 win over the Browns.

impact: With Dalvin Cook (hamstring) still sidelined, Thomas got a shot as the Vikes' No. 2 back behind Latavius Murray. He drew a red zone target and goal line carry. Perhaps the Jacksonville State UDFA is worth an add in the deepest of Dynasty leagues.
report: Roc Thomas rushed four times for eight yards in the Vikings' Week 5 win over the Eagles, adding a six-yard reception.

impact: Filling in for a suspended Jameis Winston, Fitzpatrick was sensational in his season debut, embarrassing the Saints on their home turf. The Harvard man was especially dominant in the first half, completing 11-of-14 passes for 210 yards and two touchdowns before the break while submitting a perfect 158.3 quarterback rating. The Saints’ secondary looked out of sorts on Sunday and Fitzpatrick took full advantage of their ineptitude by hurling four touchdowns including a 58-yard seed to DeSean Jackson on the Bucs’ opening drive. That was the first of two scores for D-Jax, who registered 146 yards on five catches. FitzMagic was also Tampa’s second-leading rusher and sealed the game with a 12-yard scramble late in the fourth quarter. It’s doubtful the 35-year-old will overtake Winston for the starting job but he’s certainly worked his way into the streaming conversation. Even in a daunting matchup against the Eagles next week, he could be worth a try.
report: Ryan Fitzpatrick completed 21-of-28 passes for a career-high 417 yards with four touchdowns and no interceptions while adding 36 yards and a touchdown on 12 carries Sunday in the Buccaneers’ Week 1 win over the Saints.

impact: Bucs playcaller Todd Monken came out as aggressive as ever, calling a play-action bomb on the first play from scrimmage.  DeSean Jackson smoked Jalen Mills and scored from 75 yards out.  O.J. Howard added a 75-yard catch-and-run TD, and Chris Godwin and Mike Evans both chipped in red-zone scores.  Firing on all cylinders in an entertaining offense, Fitzpatrick has earned QB1 treatment ahead of next Monday night's home date with Pittsburgh.  As the Bucs have started 2-0, it's becoming very fair to wonder if Fitzpatrick will keep the starting quarterback job when Jameis Winston's suspension ends in Week 4.
report: Ryan Fitzpatrick completed 27-of-33 passes for 402 yards, four touchdowns, and one interception in the Bucs' Week 2 win over the Eagles.

impact: Fitzpatrick became the first quarterback in league history to pass for 400 yards in three consecutive games. The night started slow for Fitzmagic and the Bucs' offense, who went into the half trailing 30-10. Tampa Bay rallied and scored the final 17 points of the evening, though, falling just one Ben Roethlisberger scramble-and-heave to JuJu Smith-Schuster away from getting the ball back and potentially pulling off the comeback win. Fitzpatrick has been absurd through three games, totaling 1,230 passing yards, 11 touchdowns, and four picks. With Jameis Winston set to return, only time will tell whether the record book's newest member will have a starting gig in Week 4.
report: Ryan Fitzpatrick completed 30-of-50 passes for 411 yards, three touchdowns, and three interceptions in the Bucs' Week 3 loss to the Steelers.

impact: Koetter strongly considered benching Fitzpatrick for Ryan Griffin (seriously) after his third interception in last week's Monday night loss to Pittsburgh. Fitzpatrick recovered after that and eventually wound up throwing for over 400 yards, but it's clear that he'll be entering Week 4 on an extremely short leash. With Fitzpatrick at risk of an in-game benching, don't be surprised if the recently-activated Jameis Winston sees action Sunday at Soldier Field.
report: According to NFL Network's Ian Rapoport, Buccaneers coach Dirk Koetter was "one or two plays away" from benching Ryan Fitzpatrick in Week 3.

impact: Fitzpatrick was reportedly only "one or two plays away" from being benched in Week 3, too. Coach Dirk Koetter pulled the trigger in Week 4 as the Bucs went into the half trailing 38-3. Fitzpatrick totaled 126 yards and one interception before riding the pine.
report: Ryan Fitzpatrick was replaced by Jameis Winston to start the third quarter in Week 4 against the Bears.

impact: Trailing 38-3 during the first half due to Mitchell Trubisky's career performance, the Bucs had no choice but to turn one dimensional and telegraph their play-calling. Fitzpatrick, who threw for 126 yards and one interception before exiting, didn't stand a chance against the Bears' pass rush. Winston will finish the game under center.
report: Jameis Winston replaced Ryan Fitzpatrick to start the third quarter.

impact: An 80% completion rate is actually impressive given that Winston was suspended and away from football during the first three weeks. He replaced Ryan Fitzpatrick, who tossed an interception in his own right, at the half and will seemingly stay under center (barring injury) for the remainder of the season. Winston will have the entire bye week to become acclimated to football again and will return in Week 6 as a sneaky low-end QB1 against the Falcons' injury-riddled secondary.
report: Jameis Winston completed 16-of-20 passes for 145 yards, one touchdown, and two picks in the Bucs' Week 4 loss to the Bears.

impact: Winston made a couple mistakes in this game, but he delivered the big fantasy performance everyone was expecting. He was sharp early, completing four of his five passes on the opening drive including a good throw to Cameron Brate for a 15-yard touchdown, but the offense fell into a lull after that. Following an interception in the second quarter, Winston bounced back to lead a big touchdown drive he capped with a 10-yard throw to O.J. Howard, and the offense was in sync from that point on. Winston did throw an end-zone interception on the first drive of the second half -- a forced pass was tipped into the air -- but he led three straight scoring drives after that to make it a game. He got Tampa in position for a potential game-winner, but a wild final play in which he took a draw up the middle before attempting a lateral fell short. Winston faces a tougher matchup next week against the Browns, but he should be in the QB1 conversation the rest of the season.
report: Jameis Winston completed 30-of-41 passes for 395 yards, four touchdowns, and two interceptions in the Bucs' Week 6 loss to the Falcons.

impact: Winston turned in one his specials where he showcased all of the positives that made him the first overall selection in the 2015 draft and all of the mistakes that keep his status as a franchise quarterback in question. Winston threw two telegraphed interceptions and a lost a fumble on a scramble, but also shook off multiple sacks and extended drives in the run game consistently all afternoon. The highlight of his day was a 14-yard touchdown run where he sacrificed his body and dove for the end zone in the second quarter. Winston has now turned in games of 395 and 365 passing yards in his two starts. 300-yard passing games are just about something we should expect weekly in this Tampa Bay passing game. Despite his propensity for turnovers each week, Winston will be a high-floor fantasy option in Week 8 on the road against the Bengals.
report: Jameis Winston completed 32-of-52 passes for 365 yards with an interception while rushing 10 times for 55 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 7 win over the Browns.

impact: Lynch's highlight came on a pitch play where he got to the perimeter of the Browns' defense and followed an impressive downfield block by Martavis Bryant to gain 59 yards.  Lynch failed to score due to repeated goal-line stuffs, but this was his biggest rushing-yardage performance since 2014 with Seattle.  Lynch now has 20 or more touches in three straight games.  In an improving Raiders offense, he will be a high-end RB2 play in Week 5 at the Chargers.
report: Marshawn Lynch rushed 20 times for 130 yards and caught 3-of-5 targets for 27 yards in the Raiders' Week 4 win over the Browns.

impact: Lynch's volume goes as the Raiders' game script goes, and the Raiders' game script got completely out of hand in this one. Jalen Richard even got involved late with Oakland in full-on catch-up mode, finishing with six catches on the day. Lynch is still averaging 15.4 carries and has received at least 18 in Oakland's three competitive games this season. With Seattle next up, Lynch should resume the RB2-usage we're accustomed to.
report: Marshawn Lynch rushed nine times for 31 yards, adding two catches for 10 yards in the Raiders' Week 5 romping by the Chargers.

impact: It was a frustrating day for the entire Raiders' offense, which would have gotten shut out if not for a garbage-time field goal to "cut the deficit" to 27-3.  Lynch has been Oakland's best offensive player, but he has been boom or bust in fantasy because the Raiders have too often found themselves in negative game script.  Lynch now draws a Week 7 bye to rest his 32-year-old legs.
report: Marshawn Lynch rushed 13 times for 45 yards and caught 3-of-5 targets for 14 yards in the Raiders' Week 6 loss to Seattle.

impact: Roethlisberger also lost two fumbles on sacks as he compiled five turnovers on the afternoon in heavy rain. Outside of the bulk yardage, his lone bright spot was a 22-yard touchdown strike to Antonio Brown in the 3rd quarter. Roethlisberger has now thrown one or fewer touchdown passes in 16 of his past 22 games on the road in early starts. Despite his poor start, Roethlisberger will be a starting fantasy option at home next week against the Chiefs.
report: Ben Roethlisberger completed 23-of-41 passes for 335 yards with one touchdowns and three interceptions in Sunday's Week 1 tie versus the Browns.

impact: Despite Roethlisberger's best efforts to appear genuinely questionable, the Steelers dropped the act on Friday. Roethlisberger is an elite play in a game that could shoot into the scoring stratosphere.
report: Ben Roethlisberger (elbow) is active for Week 2 against the Chiefs.

impact: With the Steelers down 21-0 after 13 minutes, Roethlisberger had nearly an entire afternoon of comeback mode/garbage time. The Steelers were unwatchable early on, beginning the game with two three-and-outs. Ben then got cooking, targeting Antonio Brown and JuJu Smith-Schuster a combined 36 times. He also consistently found TE Jesse James for big plays. Rookie big-play threat James Washington was heavily involved early after a Week 1 mothballing. The Steelers actually came close to pulling off the comeback, but the early deficit was too much to overcome on an afternoon where Patrick Mahomes piled up six touchdowns. Roethlisberger has an attackable matchup in the Bucs for Week 3.
report: Ben Roethlisberger completed 39-of-60 passes for 452 yards and three touchdowns in the Steelers' 42-37, Week 2 loss to the Chiefs, adding a rushing score.

impact: Roethlisberger and the Steelers' offense shook off a quick three-and-out and interception during their first two possessions to eventually take a 30-10 lead into the half. Big Ben's first touchdown was a YAC-filled 75-yard touchdown pass over the middle to emerging starter Vance McDonald, followed by touchdowns to Antonio Brown and Ryan Switzer before heading to the locker room. Pittsburgh was shutout in the second half, but Roethlisberger did enough damage early on to finish as the week's QB10. The Steelers have a divisional showdown next Sunday night against a Ravens defense that could be without both CB Jimmy Smith and LB C.J. Mosley.
report: Ben Roethlisberger completed 30-of-38 passes for 353 yards, three touchdowns, and one interception in the Steelers' Week 3 victory over the Buccaneers.

impact: Roethlisberger had a solid first half, but the Steelers' offense went in the tank over the final two quarters. His only touchdown came on an extended play to Antonio Brown from 26 yards out. It's the first game of the season Roethlisberger hasn't passed for at least 300 yards. Roethlisberger is on pace for 32 touchdowns and  21 interceptions through the first month of the season. He'll get a matchup with the Falcons in Week 5.
report: Ben Roethlisberger completed 27-of-47 passes for 274 yards with one touchdown and an interception in the Steelers' Week 5 loss to the Ravens.

impact: Roethlisberger was on track for a disappointing day before he finally got his Antonio Brown connection going in the second half. After entering the break 2-of-8 for eight yards and an interception targeting his No. 1 wideout, Ben found Brown six times for 93 yards and two scores over the final two quarters. The second was the highlight. Brown got a step on Robert Alford down the left sideline and Roethlisberger hit him in stride for a 47-yarder. Roethlisberger gets the Bengals on the road for Week 6.
report: Ben Roethlisberger completed 19-of-29 passes for 250 yards, three touchdowns and an interception in the Steelers' 41-17, Week 5 win over the Falcons.

impact: Big Ben had a clean pocket all day, not getting sacked at all, and was pretty unlucky to only have one touchdown pass.  JuJu Smith-Schuster was ruled down at the one-yard line on a play where it appeared he actually did score.  The Steelers also failed to convert a 1st-and-goal situation from the one-yard line, settling for a field goal.  Ben's lone score was a 31-yard quick slant, game-winner to Antonio Brown with 10 seconds left.  The Steelers now head into their bye week.
report: Ben Roethlisberger completed 32-of-46 passes for 369 yards and one touchdown in the Steelers' Week 6 win over the Bengals.

impact: It was a much better second outing for Graham, but he could have had an even bigger fantasy day. He just missed on two deep targets including one in which he was clearly interfered, and he had a touchdown called back on a questionable holding call. He had another chance deep down the field on a free play, but the ball was knocked away. Even so, this was a promising performance for Graham’s rest-of-season outlook. He will be a solid TE1 next week in Washington.
report: Jimmy Graham hauled in 6-of-8 targets for 95 yards in the Packers' Week 2 tie with the Vikings.

impact: The Packers had trouble getting into the red zone thanks to drops and penalties. Hence, a quiet day for Graham. At some points today, Graham looked like he was playing in full armor. He's going to need near-weekly touchdowns to be a true top-eight TE1.
report: Jimmy Graham caught 5-of-7 targets for 45 yards in the Packers' Week 3 loss to the Redskins.

impact: The score was Graham's first in a Packers uniform. Graham was left uncovered on a three-yard rollout. Graham was also the target on Aaron Rodgers' interception, tipping the ball into the air for a pick. Graham is on pace for 64/676/4. With the exception of the touchdown rate increasing, that seems entirely plausible.
report: Jimmy Graham caught 3-of-6 targets for 21 yards and a touchdown in the Packers' Week 4 win over the Bills.

impact: The 11 targets were a new season-high and second on the team to Davante Adams (12).  Graham could have had a much bigger day, as he fell down on an end-zone fade pass at the goal line and then had a 21-yard touchdown go right through his hands later in the second half.  Graham left a lot of plays on the field.  He'll remain a top-four TE1 next week against the Niners.
report: Jimmy Graham caught 6-of-11 targets for 76 yards in the Packers' Week 5 loss to the Lions.

impact: Cousins came out peppering Dalvin Cook with early targets, beating an aggressive Niners defense for chunk gains.  He later threw a dime over the top of CB Ahkello Witherspoon to hit Stefon Diggs for a 22-yard touchdown down the left sideline.  It was a perfectly-placed ball.  Cousins' second score was an 11-yard hookup to Kyle Rudolph.  He was also cooking with Adam Thielen, who had 102 yards on six grabs, killing the Niners out of the slot.  Cousins' debut couldn't have gone much better.  The 1-0 Vikings will head on the road to Green Bay in Week 2.
report: Kirk Cousins completed 20-of-36 passes for 244 yards and two touchdowns in the Vikings' 24-16, Week 1 win over the 49ers.

impact: It was a tie, but Cousins did everything he could to win this game despite facing an underrated defense. He threw a laser to Laquon Treadwell for his first score of the day, and his third was a beautiful pass to Stefon Diggs for a 75-yard touchdown, almost all of that coming in the air. He was even better with the game on the line. Despite an interception which went right through Treadwell’s hands, Cousins was able to lead the Vikings back with an eight-play touchdown drive he finished with an outstanding tight-window throw to Adam Thielen and a two-point conversion to Diggs to tie the game. He led what should have been two scoring drives in overtime, but Daniel Carlson missed both field goals including one as time expired. With Buffalo up next, Cousins will be a locked-in QB1 next week.
report: Kirk Cousins completed 35-of-48 passes for 425 yards, four touchdowns, and an interception in the Vikings' Week 2 tie with the Packers.

impact: The Vikings' offensive line didn't help matters, allowing Cousins to be blindsided and strip-sacked on the team's first two possessions. Minnesota's passing offense was playing catch-up from that point forward as Cousins was forced to attempt 55 passes under duress for the remainder of the afternoon. Cousins' lone touchdown came in garbage time when he found Kyle Rudolph in the end zone down 27-0 with less than two minutes to play. The Vikings have another tough test on the road against the Rams Thursday night.
report: Kirk Cousins completed 40-of-55 passes for 296 yards, one touchdown, and an interception in the Vikings' Week 3 loss to the Bills.

impact: Cousins also lost a fumble on a botched sideways pass. As has become a theme, Cousins was attempting and converting heat check throws in the first half. His touchdown was a three-yarder where only Adam Thielen could catch it in the end zone. Cousins has made as many "wow" passes as anyone in football so far this season. The Vikings' offense was far less effective after halftime but got back into rhythm in time to close the game out in the fourth quarter. Cousins is making hay with his elite receiver duo of Thielen and Stefon Diggs. He'll be a high-end QB1 for next week's home date with the abysmal Cardinals.
report: Kirk Cousins completed 30-of-37 passes for 301 yards and a touchdown in the Vikings' 23-21, Week 5 win over the Eagles.

impact: He added a touchdown on a seven-yard run. Cousins fumbled on a sack that was returned for a touchdown, but he was sharp in this one, completing 71 percent of his passes. Cousins' only passing TD was a perfect throw over the middle to Adam Thielen. He's now led the Vikings to consecutive wins after losing to Buffalo and the Rams. Cousins gets a matchup with the Jets in Week 7.
report: Kirk Cousins completed 24-of-34 passes for 233 yards with a touchdown and an interception in the Vikings' Week 6 win over the Cardinals.

impact: It was a struggle much of the day as both offenses really had trouble moving the ball.  At one point, both teams were a combined 0-for-12 on third downs.  Cousins, however, did throw a 34-yard touchdown to Adam Thielen on the opening drive before then hitting Aldrick Robinson for a second 34-yard score in the fourth quarter.  Both were dimes from Cousins in tight coverage.  Cousins will look to get back on track with big numbers next week against the Saints at home.
report: Kirk Cousins completed 25-of-40 passes for 241 yards and two touchdowns in the Vikings' Week 7 win over the Jets.

impact: He led the team in targets, just ahead of Nelson Agholor (12).  Ertz has been the Eagles' most-targeted pass catcher with Nick Foles under center dating back to last season.  Carson Wentz (knee) is tentatively due back for Week 3 against the Colts, however, and Wentz's return would boost Ertz's touchdown probability.  Ertz has yet to reach pay dirt on 23 targets through two games.
report: Zach Ertz caught 11-of-13 targets for 94 yards in the Eagles' Week 2 loss to Tampa Bay.

impact: Ertz and Wentz more than less picked up where they left off as Ertz lead the Eagles across the board in targets, receptions and yards. Despite failing to score through three games, Ertz leads the Eagles in targets (33), receptions (21) and receiving yardage (215). He will be a set-and-forget option next week against the Titans.
report: Zach Ertz caught 5-of-10 targets for 73 yards in Sunday's Week 3 win over the Colts.

impact: It is about what we have come to expect from Ertz, who now has at least 10 targets in every game this season. The Titans simply had no answer for him as he consistently made plays across the middle on the way to his first 100-yard game of the season. With Wentz looking better every week, Ertz will remain a high-end TE1 as long as he is healthy.
report: Zach Ertz hauled in 10-of-14 targets for 112 yards in the Eagles' Week 4 loss to the Titans.

impact: Ertz has now caught 10 passes in 3-of-5 games this season. He's on pace for 1,398 yards after entering 2018 with a career high of 853. His production has come with both Nick Foles and Carson Wentz under center and withstood the return of Alshon Jeffery. Ertz will jockey with Rob Gronkowski and Travis Kelce for the TE1 rank going forward.
report: Zach Ertz caught 10-of-11 targets for 110 yards and a touchdown in the Eagles' Week 5 loss to the Vikings.

impact: Ertz was legitimately unstoppable, relentlessly beating the Panthers’ linebackers and safeties on slants and exploiting every hole known to man in Carolina’s zone coverage. Ertz came oh-so close to a second-quarter touchdown, but he was tackled just short of the goalline.  As the NFL’s premier route-running tight end, Ertz has also been fantasy football’s most-consistent TE1. Even against the Jaguars in London in Week 8, Ertz will be a top-three option at the position at worst.
report: Zach Ertz caught 9-of-11 targets for 138 yards in the Eagles’ Week 7 loss to the Panthers.

impact: A standout all preseason, Goedert has barely been involved in the Eagles' passing game so far in real games.  It was concerning that he played behind Josh Perkins in this one.  Perkins caught four passes for 57 yards.
report: Dallas Goedert was held catch-less in the Eagles' Week 2 loss to the Bucs.

impact: After getting benched a week ago, Goedert was a huge part of the offensive game plan in Week 3. He started the game off with his first career touchdown, a 13-yard score in which he was uncovered. Despite the promising game, Goedert will not be a fantasy option heading into Week 4 against the Titans.
report: Dallas Goedert caught 7-of-7 targets for 73 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 3 win over the Colts.

impact: There was always a chance Goedert's break out performance in Week 3 was something of a fluke, and those chances grew once Alshon Jeffery was cleared to return. Goedert was not targeted in the first half of this game, and he only played around half the snaps. Goedert should have some a couple more big games this season, but predicting them will be difficult while Zach Ertz is healthy.
report: Dallas Goedert hauled in both his targets for 13 yards in the Eagles' Week 4 loss to the Titans.

impact: Goedert now has four catches for 29 yards since Alshon Jeffery's healthy return. He is off the TE2 radar until further notice.
report: Dallas Goedert caught 2-of-2 targets for 16 yards in the Eagles' Week 5 loss to the Vikings.

impact: Goedert’s involvement in Philly’s weekly game plans has been inconsistent, but he was a big part of this week’s. The Eagles got him rolling on an early 21-yard screen pass Goedert nearly took to the house, and the second-round rookie did find pay dirt later in the second quarter from one yard out. Goedert is merely a volatile TE2, but he would be a locked-in TE1 if Zach Ertz were ever to miss time.
report: Dallas Goedert caught 4-of-5 targets for 43 yards and a touchdown in the Eagles’ Week 7 loss to Carolina.

impact: His longest catch went for 21 yards. Three of Watson’s four grabs came after halftime as the Saints did their best to chip away at a 24-point deficit. The veteran carries mild streaming appeal as a proven pass-catcher in a high-scoring attack, though most weeks, the Saints will run their offense through Michael Thomas and Alvin Kamara.
report: Ben Watson corralled all four of his targets for 44 yards Sunday in New Orleans’ Week 1 loss to the Buccaneers.

impact: Watson's overall line was a disappointment, but he had a wide open touchdown opportunity in the first quarter in which he was overthrown. Through two games, Watson has just nine catches for 63 yards and is only a desperation TE2 option in Week 3 versus the Falcons.
report: Ben Watson caught 3-of-5 targets for 19 yards in Sunday's Week 2 win over the Browns.

impact: Watson made a number of contested catches including a 19-yard grab that set up a Saints field goal late in the first half. Even at his advanced age, Watson remains a physical presence and a tough matchup for opposing defenses. Still, with so many mouths to feed in New Orleans, he’s best viewed as a TE2 for fantasy purposes.
report: Benjamin Watson nabbed five-of-six targets for 71 yards Sunday in New Orleans’ Week 3 win over the Falcons.

impact: Watson dropped a seven-yard touchdown on one of his missed connections, and the Saints had to settle for one of their four first-half field goals.  It was a step back for Watson in a glorious spot.  He'll be a fringe TE1/2 next week when the Saints go back home to face the Redskins at the Superdome.
report: Ben Watson caught 1-of-3 targets for 23 yards in the Saints' Week 4 win over the Giants.

impact: Both the grabs and targets were Watson's most of the season. The score was his first of the year. Watson is averaging just 38 weekly yards, but that is more than enough to make him a weekly TE2 in a down campaign for the position.
report: Ben Watson caught 6-of-6 targets for 43 yards and a touchdown in the Saints' Week 7 win over the Ravens.

impact: Seferian-Jenkins suffered from awful touchdown luck last season in New York, and it seems to have followed him to Jacksonville. ASJ got open for a 10-yard touchdown early in the second quarter, but the play was called back on a penalty. It is a tough break, but such is life with a touchdown-or-bust fantasy option. That is what Seferian-Jenkins will be next week against the Patriots.
report: Austin Seferian-Jenkins hauled in 3-of-5 targets for 25 yards in the Jaguars' Week 1 win over the Giants.

impact: The rarest of rarities — an ASJ touchdown that was not called back. ASJ was freed by a pick play in the end zone on his four-yard score in the second quarter. The catch-and-fall specialist is averaging eight yards through his first six Jaguars receptions. He's a low-end TE2.
report: Austin Seferian-Jenkins caught 3-of-5 targets for 23 yards and a touchdown in the Jaguars' Week 2 win over the Patriots.

impact: ASJ never logs big yardage numbers and is always a touchdown-or-bust streamer option. He will draw a "revenge" matchup in Week 4 against the Jets.
report: Austin Seferian-Jenkins caught 3-of-5 targets for 18 yards in the Jaguars' Week 3 loss to Tennessee.

impact: Seferian-Jenkins wasn't much of a factor playing against his former team. He's been an afterthought in Jacksonville's offense this year, failing to go over 25 yards in any game. Seferian-Jenkins gets a matchup against the Chiefs in Week 5.
report: Austin Seferian-Jenkins caught 2-of-4 passes for 24 yards in Week 4 against the Jets.

impact: Seferian-Jenkins could not come up with the pass on a fourth-and-two target in the second quarter. That was his last involvement in the game, and he did not play many snaps if any at all in the second half. Seferian-Jenkins has been struggling with a core-muscle injury all season, and it is possible that issue flared up against Kansas City. Niles Paul, who finished with 65 yards on seven catches, would be next up at tight end.
report: Austin Seferian-Jenkins did not catch his only target in the Jaguars' Week 5 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Filling in for Austin Seferian-Jenkins, who appeared to aggravate his core-muscle injury, Paul racked up five of his catches in the second half. If ASJ is forced to miss time, Paul would get into the TE2 conversation at a desolate position.
report: Niles Paul hauled in 7-of-9 targets for 65 yards in the Jaguars' Week 5 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Backfield mate Marshawn Lynch handled just nine carries since the game was out of hand early. Richard was involved late, finishing second on the team in receiving yards. Richard has shown a propensity to produce when involved — the issue being he's never involved. If Lynch ever misses time, there's no doubt Richard will sneak into strong RB3/FLEX consideration.
report: Jalen Richard caught all six of his targets for 53 yards and one touchdown in the Raiders' Week 5 stomping to the Chargers.

impact: When the Raiders play from behind, Richard's usage spikes as a frequent checkdown target for checkdown-loving Derek Carr.  The team's leading receiver in Sunday's blowout loss, Richard will remain a negative-game-script-dependent, PPR-only flex option when Oakland emerges from its Week 7 bye.
report: Jalen Richard caught 7-of-8 targets for 48 yards and rushed twice for three yards in the Raiders' Week 6 loss to Seattle.

impact: Sharing time with Jalen Richard as the Raiders' backups to Marshawn Lynch, Martin is worth rostering in fantasy leagues only as a deep-league handcuff/stash.
report: Doug Martin managed 11 yards on five carries in the Raiders' Week 4 win.

impact: Carr was borderline flawless all afternoon, throwing just one incompletion in the first half and just three all game while averaging 8.3 yards per pass attempt. His lone touchdown was a 20-yard touchdown strike to Seth Roberts that put the Raiders up 19-7 in the 3rd quarter. Carr's Week 2 game was a big step forward after a lackluster open to the season, but will remain in the QB2 mix as Oakland heads to Miami in Week 3.
report: Derek Carr completed 29-of-32 passes for 288 yards and one touchdown in Sunday's Week 2 loss to the Broncos.

impact: Carr was awful in Week 1, solid in Week 2 and adequate today. His first interception was an end zone arm punt on a play where he had a miscommunication with Amari Cooper. His second was an inadvisable throw to a blanketed Martavis Bryant in the end zone late. Carr would have had a bigger fantasy day, but a Jared Cook touchdown came off the board when it was revealed he was down at the one-yard line. Cooper also committed an inexplicable drop. It has not been elite stuff from Carr, but he has put his brutal opener behind him. He's playing solid enough football. The Raiders just don't have much talent. The Browns will be a tough Week 4 opponent.
report: Derek Carr completed 27-of-39 passes for 345 yards, one touchdown and two interceptions in the Raiders' 28-20, Week 3 loss to the Dolphins.

impact: In a barnburning 45-42 shootout, Carr turned in his best game of the Jon Gruden era with red-zone scores to Amari Cooper, Jared Cook (two), and Jordy Nelson as Oakland shredded Cleveland's previously-stingy pass defense.  Carr has thrown for at least 288 yards in each of the Raiders' first four games, although this was his first big-time fantasy performance.  The Raiders go on the road to face the Chargers in Week 5.  In another potential shootout, Carr will be a solid two-quarterback league play with some low-end QB1 streamer appeal for fantasy leaguers in bye-week binds.
report: Derek Carr completed 35-of-58 passes for 437 yards, four touchdowns, and two interceptions in the Raiders' Week 4 overtime win over the Browns.

impact: Carr had less than 200 yards and one pick with 10 minutes remaining in the fourth quarter. A 47-yard completion to Martavis Bryant (3-91) and eventual touchdown toss to a wide-open Jordy Nelson (due to a complete breakdown in the Chargers' secondary) allowed Carr to turn an outright miserable day into one that was simply miserable. Carr has undoubtedly been poor in engineering coach Jon Gruden's otherwise efficient offense this season, but his weekly fantasy finishes are still that of a low-end QB2 with QB1 streaming appeal. The Raiders host the Seahawks in Week 6.
report: Derek Carr managed to complete 24-of-33 passes for 268 yards, one touchdown, and one interception in the Raiders' Week 5 loss to the Chargers.

impact: Carr took six sacks and lost two fumbles, and he suffered an apparent left-arm injury in the fourth quarter.  The Raiders opted to let A.J. McCarron finish out the game down 27-3.  Carr has had one productive fantasy performance out of six so far this year while repeatedly earning the ire of first-year coach Jon Gruden.  As the Raiders head into their Week 7 bye, Carr has long been droppable in 14- and even 16-team fantasy leagues.
report: Derek Carr completed 23-of-31 passes for 142 yards and rushed four times for 31 yards in the Raiders' Week 6 loss to Seattle.

impact: He was quickly ruled out for the rest of the game.  Wallace caught one pass for no gain and appeared to suffer a potentially severe injury on the play.  Wallace had a towel over his head and appeared distraught as he made his way on the cart to the locker room.  The Eagles are already without Alshon Jeffery (shoulder) and Mack Hollins (groin, I.R.).  They're down to Nelson Agholor, DeAndre Carter, Shelton Gibson, and Kamar Aiken at wideout.
report: Mike Wallace was carted off in the first quarter of Sunday's Week 2 game with an ankle injury.

impact: Agholor has double-digit targets in each of the first two weeks, and there is some belief Carson Wentz (knee) could return for Week 3 versus Indianapolis.  With Alshon Jeffery (shoulder) slated to miss at least one more game, Agholor will remain a volume monster.  He's earned WR2 treatment for the foreseeable future.
report: Nelson Agholor caught 8-of-12 targets for 95 yards and a touchdown in the Eagles' Week 2 loss at Tampa Bay.

impact: For the second time in three games, Agholor received all of his targets near the line of scrimmage and failed totally tangible receiving yardage. Through three games, Agholor has 20 receptions for a 145 yards (7.3 yards per reception). With Alshon Jefferey nearing a return, Agholor may quickly find himself third in line for targets. As for now, Agholor is a WR3/FLEX option in PPR formats in Week 4 against the Titans.
report: Nelson Agholor caught 4-of-5 targets for 24 yards in Sunday's Week 4 game versus the Colts.

impact: It was a day to forget for Agholor. He dropped at least two passes including one which would have converted a third-and-long, and he committed a bad fumble which luckily for him rolled out of bounds. On the bright side, he still saw 12 targets in Alshon Jeffery's first game back and had a couple chances at big plays. He will look to bounce back against a scuffling Vikings defense next week.
report: Nelson Agholor hauled in 5-of-12 targets for 22 yards in the Eagles' Week 4 loss to the Titans.

impact: The four targets were a new season low. Agholor is sitting on one touchdown and has cleared 50 yards once in five games. Since Carson Wentz's return, he is averaging seven targets. Agholor will be a low-end WR3 for Thursday night's game against the Giants.
report: Nelson Agholor caught 4-of-4 targets for 45 yards in the Eagles' Week 5 loss to the Vikings.

impact: This is what happens when you start the game with -1 yard on your first four targets. Quick hitters to Agholor simply did not work in this one, as the Panthers’ speedy linebackers tracked him down quickly each time. As a slot receiver, Agholor will theoretically have the Eagles’ best Week 8 pass-catcher matchup against Jacksonville, but his usage and production warrant WR4 treatment at this point.
report: Nelson Agholor caught 6-of-7 targets for 20 yards in the Eagles’ Week 7 loss to the Panthers.

impact: Jeffery had been expected to play this week after finally being cleared for contact, and there's a still possibility that he will, though an illness has slowed his progress. Considering he only practiced once this week, the Eagles may play it safe by waiting until Week 5 to unleash their star wideout. Another absence for Jeffery would be good news for slot receiver Nelson Agholor, who has drawn 27 targets in the early going.
report: NFL Network's Ian Rapoport reports Alshon Jeffery (questionable, shoulder/illness) will be a game-time decision Week 4 against the Titans.

impact: Jeffery's shoulder is fine, but he was a game-time decision after battling an illness all week. At less than 100 percent and coming off an extended layoff, the Eagles may ease him back with situational and red-zone snaps. Owners should wait another week before inserting Jeffery into lineups.
report: Alshon Jeffery (questionable, shoulder/illness) will play in Week 4 against the Titans.

impact: Jeffery missed time late in the week with an illness, but he was always expected to make his season debut this week. Coming off a long-term injury against a team which has played better defense since Week 1, Jeffery is a risky WR3 option.
report: Alshon Jeffery (shoulder) is active for Week 4 against the Titans.

impact: Jeffery's first catch did not come until the second quarter, and he appeared gassed after the 31-yard gain in his first game action this season. Tired or not, that was just the start of a big game. He had a great box-out catch on third-and-goal for his touchdown, and he earned a first down on a late game-tying drive with a catch-and-run on a screen. Now healthy and with his quarterback rounding into form, Jeffery should be considered a back-end WR2 in a suddenly promising matchup against the Vikings next week.
report: Alshon Jeffery hauled in 8-of-9 targets for 105 yards and a touchdown in the Eagles' Week 4 loss to the Titans.

impact: Jeffery nearly had a third catch on a late third down but could not hold on after taking a colossal shot to the back. It did not feel like Jeffery was getting erased by Xavier Rhodes, but the box score certainly reflects that. Jeffery figures to see more shadow treatment (Janoris Jenkins) in Week 6 when the Eagles venture to New York to take on the Giants for Thursday Night Football. He'll be on the WR2/3 borderline for that one. Jenkins is having a tough year.
report: Alshon Jeffery caught 2-of-8 targets for 39 yards in the Eagles' Week 5 loss to the Vikings.

impact: It was an easy night at the office for Jeffery, who benefitted from Carson Wentz's play-making ability on the run. Jeffery had few issues with Janoris Jenkins' coverage. The Eagles' No. 1 receiver is up to three scores in three games since making his 2018 debut. He'll be a back-end WR2 for next week's date with the Panthers.
report: Alshon Jeffery caught 8-of-12 targets for 74 yards and two touchdowns in the Eagles' Week 6 win over the Giants.

impact: Through no fault of Jeffery’s, the Eagles wound up losing this game despite building a 17-0 halftime lead. Jeffery dominated his matchup against Panthers CB James Bradberry, frequently looking like a man among boys and whipping Bradberry for an early 11-yard touchdown on an inside move. Alshon has been an elite producer since returning from his shoulder injury. He will face a talented but downward-spiraling Jaguars defense next.
report: Alshon Jeffery caught 7-of-10 targets for 88 yards and a touchdown in the Eagles’ Week 7 loss to Carolina.

impact: He added a two-point conversion, but it was another disappointing fantasy day for Kittle. He made a couple big plays including one in which he ran over a defensive back in the third quarter, but he dropped what would have been a big gain in the first quarter and had a touchdown called back on a questionable offensive pass interference call. Even worse, it looks like Jimmy Garoppolo is dealing with a season-ending knee injury. If that turns out to be the case, Kittle will be downgraded to a low-end TE1 option moving forward.
report: George Kittle hauled in 5-of-7 targets for 79 yards in the 49ers' Week 3 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: C.J. Beathard showered Kittle with a team-high eight targets in the first 49ers game post-Garoppolo. Kittle was being held in check until he escaped over the middle for an 82-yard touchdown late in the third quarter. The 49ers were without receivers Marquise Goodwin and Dante Pettis for much of the game after they suffered leg injuries, and Kittle would get a bump if they miss next week's game against the Cardinals. Kittle is still in the TE1 mix even with Garoppolo out for the season.
report: George Kittle caught six passes for 125 yards and one touchdown in the 49ers' Week 4 loss to the Chargers.

impact: Kittle was responsible for San Francisco's longest play of the afternoon, breaking off a 45-yard catch-and-run down the right sideline with a little under 10 minutes to go in the fourth quarter. Garbage time was Kittle's ally on Sunday as the tight end went for 62 yards on three catches with the Niners playing from behind in the second half. Kittle has shown a strong rapport with quarterback C.J. Beathard, which is nothing new since the two were college teammates together at Iowa. The 24-year-old has given fantasy owners a surprisingly consistent floor this year, eclipsing 75 yards in four of five games. He'll look to make it five out of six next week at Green Bay.
report: George Kittle earned five catches for 83 yards on seven targets Sunday in the 49ers’ Week 5 loss to Arizona.

impact: Maiocco is simply reading the tea leaves.  But it makes sense.  Either that or the Niners are just protecting themselves in case Kittle proves in pregame warmups that he's not going to be able to play.  Kittle got in a week of limited practices, suggesting he should be able to gut it out.  Inactives for this one should be out around 6:45 PM ET.  Kittle owners may need a backup plan.
report: NBC Bay Area's Matt Maiocco believes the promotion of TE Ross Dwelley from the practice squad suggests George Kittle (knee) may be inactive Monday night against the Packers.

impact: The Niners promoted TE Ross Dwelley from the practice squad on Monday, causing a bit of concern about Kittle's status for Week 6.  But it sounds like he's good to go after a week of limited practices.  Perhaps the Niners will dial back Kittle's snaps some and give Garrett Celek a bit more run.  Schefter adds both Matt Breida (ankle) and Pierre Garcon (shoulder) are also expected to play.
report: ESPN's Adam Schefter reports George Kittle (knee) is expected to play Monday night against the Packers.

impact: Matt Breida (ankle) and Pierre Garcon (shoulder, knee) are also active.  Kittle could have his snaps scaled back some but remains a lock-and-load TE1.
report: George Kittle (knee) is active for Week 6 against the Packers on Monday night.

impact: Kittle was the offense for most of this game. He sparked the only scoring drive of the first half with a 23-yard gain in the second quarter and finished the drive with a 10-yard touchdown catch. He had 77 of C.J. Beathard’s 106 yards at the break. The offense's futility limited him in the second half, but he still got loose for a 21-yard gain in the third quarter. Kittle has now topped 75 yards in five of seven games and has two touchdowns in his last four. He will be a high-end TE1 next week in Arizona.
report: George Kittle hauled in 5-of-8 targets for 98 yards and a touchdown in the 49ers' Week 7 loss to the Rams.

impact: Westbrook did not get the start, but he looked like Blake Bortles' No. 1 option for stretches of this game including on back-to-back big catches in the second quarter. Westbrook's six targets were the second-most on the team and the most among the receiving corps. It is only a matter of time before he jumps Donte Moncrief on the depth chart.
report: Dede Westbrook hauled in 5-of-6 targets for 51 yards in the Jaguars' Week 1 win over the Giants.

impact: Westbrook also lost six yards on a rush. It would have been a lost day for Westbrook, but he managed to turn a fourth quarter dumpoff into a 61-yard touchdown. Westbrook shed a tackle, found the sideline and was off to the races. Those are the kinds of plays he's capable of. Westbrook's upside is tantalizing, but the Jags' receiver rotation currently has him stuck in WR4 land for fantasy purposes.
report: Dede Westbrook caught 4-of-5 targets for 83 yards and a touchdown in the Jaguars' Week 2 win over the Patriots.

impact: Westbrook has been expectedly inconsistent in the early going as a rotational receiver on a run-first team.  He will get a better matchup in Week 4 against the Jets, who have struggled mightly to contain slot receivers.
report: Dede Westbrook caught 3-of-4 targets for 31 yards in the Jaguars' Week 3 loss to Tennessee.

impact: Westbrook started fast, racking up six catches for 89 yards in the first half. He led Jacksonville in targets, ahead of both Keelan Cole (3) and Donte Moncrief (5). Westbrook did most of his damage on short passes but was explosive in the open field and picked up most of his yards after the catch. He's now went over 80 yards in two of his last three games. Westbrook will be a WR3/FLEX for Week 5 against the Chiefs.
report: Dede Westbrook caught 9-of-13 targets for 130 yards in Jacksonville's Week 4 win over the Jets.

impact: Held off the box score in the first half, Westbrook opened the third quarter with a 30-yard catch and converted a third down with a great 23-yard grab on the next drive. That was about it for the receiver, however, who still served as the No. 3 despite his breakout game last week. Westbrook will be a weak WR4 dart throw next week in Dallas.
report: Dede Westbrook hauled in 3-of-5 targets for 55 yards in the Jaguars' Week 5 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Like the rest of Jacksonville's sluggish offense, Westbrook was mostly held in check, though he did find an opening in the Cowboys' defense during the third quarter when he scored on a 34-yard touchdown pass from Blake Bortles. Even with Sunday's clunker thrown in, the second-year wideout is still on pace for over 1,000 yards receiving. He'll get the Texans at home in Week 7.
report: Dede Westbrook secured three catches for 38 yards and a touchdown on five targets Sunday in the Jaguars’ Week 6 loss to Dallas.

impact: Westbrook got loose for no big plays as the Jaguars switched quarterbacks, benching Blake Bortles for Cody Kessler early in the third quarter. Donte Moncrief, T.J. Yeldon, Keelan Cole, and rookie D.J. Chark all drew more targets than Westbrook, who will be a dicey WR4/flex option when the Jaguars head to London to face the Eagles next.
report: Dede Westbrook caught 4-of-4 targets for 17 yards in the Jaguars’ Week 7 loss to the Texans.

impact: The 49ers' slot receiver, Taylor's six targets were tied with Pierre Garcon for second on the team behind George Kittle (9).  However, Taylor is more of a Cole Beasley type who will have a big game here or there but isn't fantasy-relevant outside of deep PPR leagues.  Leave Taylor on the wire.
report: Trent Taylor caught 4-of-6 targets for 28 yards in the 49ers' Week 1 loss to the Vikings.

impact: Even with Marquise Goodwin (quad) on the shelf, the second-year slot man failed to make an impact. Taylor had his moments as a rookie but is off to a quiet start this year with just four catches for 28 yards on eight targets. Outside of dynasty leagues, Taylor doesn’t offer much fantasy appeal.
report: Trent Taylor came up empty on both of his targets Sunday in San Francisco’s Week 2 win over the Lions.

impact: Two words: garbage time. Taylor snoozed through the first half, securing his lone target for a two-yard pickup. But with San Francisco behind in the second half, the young slot receiver feasted with six catches including four on the Niners' final drive. Taylor was also the recipient of a one-yard touchdown, which capped a 14-play, 82-yard drive in the fourth quarter. That play came on a successful fourth-down conversion. Taylor entered Sunday's action with 64 yards all SEASON, so this isn't something fantasy owners should grow accustomed to. The second-year La Tech alum gets the Packers on the road in Week 6.
report: Trent Taylor delivered seven catches for 61 yards and a touchdown on eight targets Sunday in San Francisco’s Week 5 loss to the Cardinals.

impact: The 49ers were stuck with just three active receivers for much of the game with Marquise Goodwin and Dante Pettis both leaving the game early with knee injuries. Garcon was still unable to do much with the extra looks, as has been the case all year. Through four weeks, Garcon has 14 receptions for 156 scoreless yards, and he's has failed to score 10 PPR points in a game despite Goodwin being in-and-out of the lineup.
report: Pierre Garcon caught 4-of-7 targets for 52 scoreless yards in the 49ers' Week 4 loss to the Chargers.

impact: He dropped at least two of those targets. This was easily Garcon's biggest workload of 2018, though obviously he wasn't able to take advantage. Even with Marquise Goodwin injured, Garcon has done next to nothing, reeling in just 16-of-33 targets (48.5 percent) for 188 scoreless yards this season. The 32-year-old will take a 16-game touchdown drought into next week's matchup at Green Bay.
report: Pierre Garcon managed five catches for 47 yards on 12 targets Sunday in the Niners’ Week 5 loss to the Cardinals.

impact: Garcon isn't 100 percent after barely practicing this week, but he's going to gut it out.  With the Niners likely to be playing catchup most of the night, Garcon has some WR4 appeal in deeper leagues.
report: Pierre Garcon (shoulder, knee) is active Week 6 against the Packers.

impact: There wasn't much doubt over his status. Garcon should see a few more targets with Trent Taylor (back) questionable. He's our No. 54-ranked wideout this week.
report: Pierre Garcon (knee, shoulder) is expected to play in Week 7 against the Rams.

impact: With C.J. Beathard struggling, Garcon never had a chance. He has still failed to top 60 yards in any game this season, and he has scored a touchdown since Week 14 of the 2016 season. He can be left on the wire.
report: Pierre Garcon took his only target five yards in the 49ers' Week 7 loss to the Rams.

impact: Moncrief got the start and actually saw one more target than Keelan Cole, but he was easily the least productive member of the receiving corps. Moncrief should remain involved because of his red-zone ability, but it would not be surprising if Dede Westbrook jumped him on the depth chart.
report: Donte Moncrief hauled in 1-of-5 targets for 14 yards in the Jaguars' Week 1 win over the Giants.

impact: There's a Moncrief line if we've ever seen one. Moncrief's four-yard score was a nice grab against tight Stephon Gilmore coverage in the end zone. Moncrief was announced with a knee injury in the second half but ended up playing through it. Despite the team-leading nine targets, Moncrief was fourth in yardage. He's a touchdown-or-bust WR4 for fantasy purposes.
report: Donte Moncrief caught 4-of-9 targets for 34 yards and a touchdown in the Jaguars' Week 2 win over the Patriots.

impact: Moncrief is a rotational receiver on a run-first team with a highly inconsistent quarterback.  He is barely roster worthy in 12-team leagues.
report: Donte Moncrief caught 2-of-3 targets for 16 yards in the Jaguars' Week 3 loss to Tennessee.

impact: Moncrief got behind Jets CB Trumaine Johnson for a 67-yard TD. It was his only real highlight, though Moncrief saw the second most targets behind Dede Westbrook. Moncrief didn't have more than 34 yards in any game prior to this week. This will likely go down as one of his best games.
report: Donte Moncrief caught five passes for 109 yards and a touchdowin in Week 4 against the Jets.

impact: Moncrief led the team in receiving, but there was nothing particularly impactful about his performance. He had 15 yards at the half, and 25 of his yards came on a meaningless catch deep into garbage time. That said, he remains at worst the No. 2 option in a passing game which has created a lot of yardage with Leonard Fournette sidelined. He will be on the desperation WR4 map next week in Dallas.
report: Donte Moncrief hauled in 6-of-15 targets for 76 yards in the Jaguars' Week 5 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Moncrief entered Week 6 with 11 catches for 185 yards and a touchdown over his previous two outings, but that all went out the window against Dallas. The ex-Colt blew a fourth-down conversion with an ugly drop in the fourth quarter, not that it mattered much with Jacksonville getting boat-raced. Moncrief's goose egg Sunday serves as a reminder that he'll always be a boom-or-bust fantasy player. We'll see how he fares against Houston in Week 7.
report: Donte Moncrief came up empty on his three targets Sunday in Jacksonville’s Week 6 loss to the Cowboys.

impact: Moncrief led the team in targets and receiving in a game where Blake Bortles was benched for losing multiple fumbles, and Cody Kessler wound up attempting 30 passes in a half as the Jaguars played from behind. The week before, Moncrief went catch-less on three targets. Although Week 8 against the Eagles poses a favorable matchup, Moncrief’s wild week-to-week inconsistency will render him a boom-bust WR3/flex option.
report: Donte Moncrief caught 7-of-10 targets for 76 yards in the Jaguars’ Week 7 loss to the Texans.

impact: Cole got off to a great start with a 31-yard catch on the second play of the game, but he was mostly quiet as Blake Bortles struggled the rest of the way. He did lead the Jaguars with 54 yards, but Dede Westbrook paced the receivers with 6 targets. Cole will remain an upside WR4 play next week against the Patriots.
report: Keelan Cole hauled in 3-of-4 targets for 54 yards in the Jaguars' Week 1 win over the Giants.

impact: After a quiet Week 1, Cole delivered on his summer hype, giving him three 100-yard games over his past five regular season contests. The highlights were in the first quarter, where Cole made a one-handed, Odell Beckham-esque 22-yard catch on Eric Rowe down the sideline. He finished the job by dismantling Rowe for a 24-yard score three plays later. Cole is simply a born playmaker down the field. The Jags' receiver rotation will make him uneven in fantasy, but he's earned the right to be treated as an every-week WR3.
report: Keelan Cole caught 7-of-8 targets for 116 yards and a touchdown in the Jaguars' Week 2 win over the Patriots.

impact: Cole led the Jags in targets, but Blake Bortles' wild inaccuracies returned, and Jacksonville got nothing going in the downfield passing game.  Cole has an abundance of talent, but this offense is simply not worthy of trust for him to be viewed as anything more than a volatile WR3/flex option in Week 4 versus the Jets.
report: Keelan Cole caught 5-of-9 targets for 40 yards in the Jaguars' Week 3 loss to Tennessee.

impact: It was a quiet game for Cole with Dede Westbrook and Donte Moncrief both going over 100 yards. Cole made both of his catches in the first quarter and was a non-factor in the second half. He's now been held under 40 yards in back to back games. The Jagaurs spread it out offense is going to be dificult to predict on a week to week basis. Cole will just be a low-end WR3 for Week 5.
report: Keelan Cole caught 2-of-3 passes for 15 yards in Week 4 against the Jets.

impact: Cole played a big role in the Jaguars' only good drive of the game, hauling in a 32-yard pass to help set up a touchdown on the next play. He also drew a deep target at the end of the first half, but it was a non-descript game for Jacksonville's 1A receiver. He will be just a WR4 play next week in Dallas.
report: Keelan Cole hauled in 4-of-10 targets for 70 yards in the Jaguars' Week 5 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Three of his grabs came with Jacksonville down big in the second half. Cole was stripped by Jaylen Smith in the third quarter, resulting in a turnover. It's been a quiet stretch for the second-year wideout, who has topped 50 yards just once during his current four-game touchdown drought. Cole is just a bench stash at this point.
report: Keelan Cole collected four catches for 41 yards on five targets Sunday in the Jags’ Week 6 loss to the Cowboys.

impact: It was an inefficient day for Cole as the Jaguars benched Blake Bortles and turned to game-manager backup Cody Kessler for 30 second-half pass attempts. Even in a favorable matchup, Cole will be a low-floor WR4 option as the Jaguars head to London for Week 8 to face the Eagles.
report: Keelan Cole caught 2-of-7 targets for 21 yards in the Jaguars’ Week 7 loss to the Texans.

impact: Hopefully you took the over in this game, because it was a slugfest. Ginn got off to a strong start, capping the Saints’ opening drive with a four-yard touchdown on a play-action pass from Drew Brees. Aside from that play and a 20-yard rush on an end-around in the fourth quarter, the veteran was mostly held in check. Ginn dropped a pair of passes in the first half, which may explain why he wasn’t targeted after halftime. He’ll look to get back on track next week when the Saints travel to East Rutherford for a date with the 1-2 Giants.
report: Ted Ginn absorbed three-of-six targets for 12 yards and a touchdown while amassing 20 yards on his lone rushing attempt Sunday in the Saints’ Week 3 win over the Falcons.

impact: He rushed one time for one yard.  Ginn almost had the Saints in serious hot water late in the fourth quarter when he botched a kickoff ahead by eight points, setting the offense up at their own three-yard line.  But Alvin Kamara ended up scoring from 49 yards out to alleviate any concerns.  Ginn is a boom-or-bust WR4.
report: Ted Ginn failed to catch any of his three targets in the Saints' Week 4 win over the Giants.

impact: It was an improvement on the four touches Montgomery saw in Week 1, but he still has been mostly uninvolved through two weeks. More worryingly, Aaron Jones is due back from suspension in Week 3. Montgomery is not a must-roster player in standard scoring.
report: Ty Montgomery rushed five times for 31 yards and caught 1-of-2 targets for nine yards in the Packers' Week 2 tie with the Vikings.

impact: With Aaron Rodgers' receivers struggling to make big plays, TyMont finally got involved as a pass catcher/outlet. Both his 10 touches and 64 yards led the Packers' three-man backfield. Especially with Randall Cobb struggling, the Pack figure to work on getting Montgomery more involved on a weekly basis. The Bills are an appetizing Week 4 matchup.
report: Ty Montgomery caught 6-of-7 targets for 48 yards in the Packers' Week 3 loss to the Redskins, adding four carries for 16 additional yards.

impact: Most of Montgomery's yardage came when he got a free release down the left sideline for a 43-yard catch in the first quarter. The Pack's backfield remained a three-man rotation this afternoon, with Aaron Jones winning both the touch and yardage battles. Montgomery will continue to struggle for value outside of PPR leagues.
report: Ty Montgomery caught 2-of-3 targets for 56 yards in the Packers' Week 4 win over the Bills, adding five rushes for 18 additional yards.

impact: Montgomery got a ton of playing time in the second half with the Packers in catchup mode.  He has no fantasy value outside of deeper PPR leagues.
report: Ty Montgomery rushed four times for 15 yards in the Packers' Week 5 loss to the Lions, adding a 23-yard catch on three targets.

impact: Njoku saw the second-most targets on the team, but had a hard time converting them into anything tangible. He had two drops in the third quarter on back-to-back plays that thwarted a Cleveland drive. Njoku remains an upside option for fantasy in Week 2 versus the Saints, but is far from established as a entrenched fantasy starter at this stage.
report: Browns TE David Njoku caught 3-of-7 targets for 13 yards in Sunday's Week 1 game versus the Steelers.

impact: Njoku matched a team-high seven targets, but was a letdown for the second consecutive week for fantasy purposes. Through two weeks, he's now secured just 7-of-14 targets for 33 yards. Despite the back-to-back down games, his target volume is still tangible for a depressed fantasy position. Until he starts to turn that into production however, Njoku is only a TE2 option in Week 3 versus the Jets.
report: David Njoku caught 4-of-7 targets for 20 yards in Sunday's Week 2 loss to the Saints.

impact: It could have been a bigger day if not for Njoku committing his third drop of the season in the second half.  Nevertheless, Baker Mayfield has helped Njoku immensely after the high-upside tight end managed 33 scoreless yards on 12 targets from Tyrod Taylor in the first 2 1/2 games of the season.  Since Mayfield took over the offense, Njoku has caught seven of the rookie quarterback's nine targets for 88 yards.  Njoku will stay on the TE1 fringe when the Browns host the Ravens next.
report: David Njoku caught 5-of-7 targets for 52 yards in the Browns' Week 4 loss to the Raiders.

impact: Njoku set season-highs across the board in targets, catches and yards on Sunday. As good as his game was, he could've had much more as he suffered two dropped passes in the game. The move to Baker Mayfield has energized Njoku  as he now has 11 catches for 111 yards on 18 targets the past two weeks after nine catches for 69 yards through the opening three weeks. Despite failing to score on the season, Njoku will be a starting option at a depressed tight end position Week 6 against the Chargers.
report: David Njoku caught 6-of-11 targets for 69 yards in Sunday's Week 5 win over the Ravens.

impact: Njoku found the end zone for the first time this season in the 4th quarter on a 1-yard touchdown pass with the game way out of hand. It was Njoku's first red zone target on the season. After a season-high 11 targets last week, Njoku received 12 more looks on Sunday, giving him 30 total targets over Baker Mayfield's three starts. Njoku is in a dream spot next week against a Tampa Bay defense that has allowed the most receiving yards per game to opposing tight ends to begin the season.
report: David Njoku caught 7-of-12 targets for 55 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 6 loss to the Chargers.

impact: Njoku was held without a catch in the first half on Sunday, dropping his lone target over the opening two quarters. In the second half, he got the Browns going right away, catching a 15-yard touchdown over Adarius Taylor to get the Browns within a score. Njoku has now established himself firmly as the number two option behind Jarvis Landry in the Cleveland offense. Since Baker Mayfield has taken over, Njoku has reeled in 22-of-35 targets for 228 yards and two touchdowns. Njoku draws another positive matchup in Week 8 against the Steelers.
report: David Njoku caught 4-of-6 targets for 52 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 7 loss to the Buccaneers.

impact: Higgins led Cleveland in receiving yards in a game where Baker Mayfield spread the ball around.  David Njoku's five catches led the team.  Higgins has a secure role in three-receiver sets alongside Jarvis Landry and Antonio Callaway but lacks fantasy value outside of Dynasty leagues.
report: Rashard Higgins caught 4-of-5 targets for 61 yards in the Browns' Week 4 loss to the Raiders.

impact: Higgins was having a productive day, catching 3-of-4 targets for 66 yards and a touchdown. His 19-yard touchdown before the first half put the Browns up 6-3 at the half.
report: Rishard Higgins suffered a knee injury in Sunday's Week 5 game versus the Ravens and his return is doubtful.

impact: With Ted Ginn (knee) out, Smith saw an increased role and made the most of his three looks.  He scored the 62-yard touchdown where he was literally wide open with no defender within 10 yards of him.  It was the pass play that Brees became the NFL's all-time passing yards leader, passing Peyton Manning.  Smith wasn't done, though, as he reeled in a total dime from Brees for a 35-yard score in the third quarter.  Smith is an exciting Dynasty prospect but figures to play a low-volume role when Ginn is back healthy.  There are just so many mouths to feed.
report: Tre'Quan Smith caught all three of his targets for 111 yards and two touchdowns in the Saints' Week 5 win over the Redskins on Monday night.
