impact: Smith almost made a one-handed catch in the end zone in the first quarter but couldn't haul it in. It was a quiet day thereafter, though Smith made an excellent sideline grab. He has six receptions on nine targets in two contests with Ted Ginn sidelined. Drew Brees is averaging just 30 attempts in two games since Mark Ingram's return, and the Saints are headed on the road to take on the Vikings' tough defense in Week 8. It could be a minute before Smith becomes a legitimate WR4.
report: Tre'Quan Smith caught 3-of-6 targets for 44 yards in the Saints' Week 7 win over the Ravens.

impact: The Saints plan to work Meredith into their gameplan after making him a healthy scratch the first two weeks. It's hard to see Meredith having much of a role, but this is a step in the right direction. Meredith will push Tre'Quan Smith and Austin Carr for snaps.
report: Cameron Meredith is active for Week 3 against the Falcons.

impact: Active for the first time this season, Meredith made the most of his lone target. Meredith’s 11-yarder staked New Orleans to a 23-21 lead with just over six minutes remaining in the third quarter. The 26-year-old cleared one hurdle by recording his first catch in over 20 months, but he’s still not worthy of fantasy consideration. Meredith will try to take another step forward against the Giants in Week 4.
report: Cameron Meredith registered an 11-yard touchdown on his lone target Sunday in the Saints’ Week 3 win over the Falcons.

impact: Meredith caught his lone target for an 11-yard score in his 2018 debut last week and was more involved this Sunday.  The stat line isn't sexy, but Meredith should continue to push for heavy snaps behind Michael Thomas.  He'll again be on the WR4/5 map next week at home against the Redskins.
report: Cameron Meredith caught 3-of-4 targets for 32 yards in the Saints' Week 4 win over the Giants.

impact: It's a step back for Meredith after he went 5-of-5 for 71 yards in Week 5. Drew Brees' volume has been down during that span — coinciding with Mark Ingram's return — and Tre'Quan Smith has looked like the biggest beneficiary of Ted Ginn's absence. Meredith isn't much of a WR5 for the time being.
report: Cameron Meredith was not targeted in the Saints' Week 7 win over the Ravens.

impact: It was a balanced effort for Thomas, who recorded exactly eight catches for 90 yards in both halves. Thomas capped the second quarter with a six-yard touchdown grab on a play where the Bucs left him completely open. He nearly scored again in the fourth quarter, but was stopped just short of the goal line. Even at full strength the Bucs would have had a hard time defending Thomas, but with Brent Grimes (groin) out and Vernon Hargreaves exiting in the second half, Tampa Bay’s weakened secondary didn’t have a prayer. The third-year stud should stuff the stat sheet again in next week’s home matchup against the Browns.
report: Michael Thomas delivered a team-record 16 catches for 180 yards and a touchdown on 17 targets Sunday in the Saints’ Week 1 loss to the Buccaneers.

impact: Thomas did lose a fumble for the second straight game, but that was his only blemish on a nearly perfect day. Thomas scored both of the Saints' touchdowns, catching a 2-yard score in the third quarter to pull the Saints within a score and then catching a 5-yard touchdown over Denzel Ward to give New Orleans a lead with 2:40 left in the fourth quarter. Thomas now has reeled in 28 receptions through two weeks, which is the most for any player through two weeks in NFL history. Thomas will be a set and forget WR1 option next week when the Saints head to Atlanta.
report: Michael Thomas caught 12-of-13 targets for 89 yards and two touchdowns in Sunday's Week 2 win over the Browns.

impact: Thomas set the tone with a 35-yard gain on the Saints’ first play from scrimmage. He never managed to find the end zone but was always there when Drew Brees needed him. Thomas played a pivotal role in overtime, moving the chains with three catches for 38 yards on the game-clinching drive. Sunday’s 10-spot gives Thomas 38 catches for the year, an NFL record through the first three games. He’s also been incredibly efficient, absorbing an impossible 95 percent of his targets this year. Even with Janoris Jenkins likely to shadow him in Week 4, the red-hot Thomas will remain an appealing WR1 against the Giants.
report: Michael Thomas pulled in all 10 of his targets for 129 receiving yards Sunday in the Saints’ Week 3 victory over Atlanta.

impact: Thomas tallied at least 10 catches and/or one touchdown in each of the first three games entering Sunday.  His four targets were tied with Cameron Meredith for second on the team behind Alvin Kamara's nine, and Drew Brees didn't throw a single touchdown as Kamara rushed for three.  Thomas should bounce back no problem back at home against the Redskins in Week 5.
report: Michael Thomas caught all four of his targets for 47 yards in the Saints' Week 4 win over the Giants.

impact: After seeing 40 combined targets Weeks 1-3, Thomas has been targeted a total of nine times the past two weeks and hasn't scored in either game.  He was obviously never going to continue at that ridiculous three-week pace, but there are so many talented players in this offense with the emergence of Tre'Quan Smith (3-111-2 tonight) and return of Mark Ingram that the Saints can spread the ball around.  Thomas will get a difficult matchup on the road against the Ravens in Week 7 when the Saints come off their bye.
report: Michael Thomas caught 4-of-5 targets for 74 yards in the Saints' Week 5 win over the Redskins.

impact: The catches were Thomas' most since Week 3, while the score was his first since Week 2. Surprisingly, Thomas has failed to clear 10 targets or 75 yards in each of his past three games. He has a tough Week 8 matchup in Xavier Rhodes and the Vikings, though Rhodes could end up missing the game with an ankle injury.
report: Michael Thomas caught 7-of-9 targets for 69 yards and a touchdown in the Saints' Week 7 win over the Ravens.

impact: With Marquise Goodwin going down very early in the second quarter with a quad injury, Pettis was the next man up opposite Pierre Garcon with Trent Taylor in the slot.  Pettis scored the Niners' lone touchdown, making an over-the-shoulder catch from 22 yards out on an escape maneuver by Jimmy Garoppolo outside the pocket.  Pettis will be on the fantasy map if Goodwin misses time.
report: Dante Pettis caught 2-of-5 targets for 61 yards and one touchdown in the 49ers' Week 1 loss to the Vikings.

impact: Pettis dusted Teez Tabor for a 35-yard gain in the first quarter but wasn’t heard from again. The rookie was expected to play an important role with Marquise Goodwin (quad) sidelined this week, but obviously that didn’t come to fruition. Even with a likely shootout on tap next week at Kansas City, the rookie will be difficult to trust in fantasy.
report: Dante Pettis was limited to one catch for 35 yards on two targets Sunday in San Francisco’s Week 2 win over the Lions.

impact: With Marquise Goodwin healthy, Pettis disappeared from the game plan. He can be dropped in redraft leagues.
report: Dante Pettis was not targeted in the 49ers' Week 3 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Pettis was met by multiple Chargers directly after catching a punt, but he quickly went down in an odd play that left Pettis without one of his cleats. The 49ers training staff checked the stability of his knee on the field before taking him to the sideline. With Marquise Goodwin healthy, Pettis was not targeted last week.
report: Dante Pettis suffered a left knee injury in the 49ers' Week 4 game against the Chargers and is questionable to return.

impact: Pettis suffered a knee injury on a punt return and he needed assistance from the training staff to get off the field. The timing of the injury is bad with Marquise Goodwin (leg) in the locker room. The 49ers only have Pierre Garcon, Trent Taylor, and Kendrick Bourne at receiver at the moment. The 49ers have also ruled out LT Joe Staley (knee) for the remainder of the game. Finally, RT Mike McGlinchey is questionable to return.
report: Dante Pettis has been ruled out for the remainder of the 49ers' Week 4 game against the Chargers.

impact: Goodwin was put through a workout before the game, so he apparently showed enough to be active. There is still some concern he will be used less than usual after missing last week, but the matchup could not be better. Goodwin should be in fantasy lineups.
report: Marquise Goodwin (quad) is active for Week 3 against the Chiefs.

impact: Goodwin entered the game questionable with a quad injury, but he did not look hampered on the field. His touchdown came when he was left wide open in the third quarter, and Jimmy Garoppolo found him for an 11-yard score. Unfortunately, Garoppolo suffered what appears to be a season-ending injury in the fourth quarter. That is a concern for Goodwin, who broke out with Garoppolo under center late last season, but he also had some big games with C.J. Beathard on the field. He should stick in the WR3 tier.
report: Marquise Goodwin hauled in 3-of-4 targets for 30 yards and a touchdown in the 49ers' Week 3 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Goodwin might have re-injured his quad but that's unconfirmed. He was taken into the locker room after reaching for his leg on a late second quarter play. Goodwin's direct replacement Dante Pettis (knee) left the game earlier and his return is questionable. The 49ers wide receiver depth is being tested in Los Angeles.
report: Marquise Goodwin exited from the 49ers' Week 4 game against the Chargers with a leg injury.

impact: Battling quad and hamstring issues much of the first five weeks, Goodwin entered Monday with a combined five catches for 54 yards and one score in three games played.  This game came out of nowhere, but Goodwin can do this anytime he steps on the field when healthy.  He ran right by CB Kentrell Brice for a 67-yard touchdown in the first quarter before then beating veteran Tramon Williams for a 30-yard score nine minutes later.  Where Goodwin was dropped in fantasy, he needs to be picked up immediately.  He'll be a WR3/4 next week against the Rams.
report: Marquise Goodwin caught 4-of-5 targets for 126 yards and two touchdowns in the 49ers' 33-30, Week 6 loss to the Packers on Monday night.

impact: Goodwin left the game briefly with a lower-leg injury, but he was able to return and catch two passes deep into garbage time. It was a disappointing follow up to his 126-yard, two-touchdown explosion on Monday night, but it is promising he easily led the receivers with five targets. The matchup next week in Arizona is not great, but Goodwin will be worth a look as a WR3.
report: Marquise Goodwin hauled in 2-of-5 targets for 24 yards in the 49ers' Week 7 loss to the Rams.

impact: Even with Leonard Fournette leaving with an injury, Grant did not see much action against the Giants. Perhaps that changes if Fournette is forced to miss time, but T.J. Yeldon is the back to add.
report: Corey Grant rushed once for three yards in the Jaguars' Week 1 win over the Giants.

impact: Grant ended up forming a near-even committee with T.J. Yeldon in Leonard Fournette's absence. The Jags worked hard to exploit Grant's play-making ability as a pass catcher. He was a spark plug who picked up a number of key first downs. Despite his big-play ability, Grant will be a low-end RB3/FLEX if Fournette remains sidelined for Week 3 against the Titans.
report: Corey Grant caught 6-of-7 targets for 56 yards in the Jaguars' Week 2 win over the Patriots, adding four rushes for 13 additional yards.

impact: Grant started the game in place of Leonard Fournette (hamstring), but the Jags wound up going with T.J. Yeldon because Grant was so ineffective.  Grant was barely even seen in the second half, while Yeldon finished with 13 touches to Grant's 7.  All in all, it was an abysmal offensive effort from a Jaguars team that played so well versus New England the week prior.  Fournette was close to playing and figures to return in Week 4 against the Jets.
report: Corey Grant rushed six times for 11 yards and caught 1-of-2 targets for a combined loss of one yard in the Jaguars' Week 3 loss to Tennessee.

impact: Grant had his lower leg caught underneath a tackler at the end of a second-quarter run. He was not able to put weight on his left leg as he was helped off the field, and he was pretty quickly ruled out. With Leonard Fournette inactive, T.J. Yeldon should get as much work as he can handle against the Chiefs. Brandon Wilds is Jacksonville's other active running back.
report: Corey Grant exited Week 5 against the Chiefs with a foot injury.

impact: Grant had to be carted off the field Sunday.  He was hyped up over the summer as someone the Jaguars wanted to get more involved in the offense, but it never really happened as Grant got 13 carries and turned them into 40 scoreless yards.  Grant nabbed nine catches for 67 yards.  He'll be a 27-year-old free agent next March coming off one of the most serious foot injuries.
report: ESPN's Adam Schefter reports Corey Grant suffered a Lisfranc injury Week 5 against the Chiefs and is expected to miss the remainder of the season.

impact: The second-year UDFA was sprung into extra snaps with Marquise Goodwin and Dante Pettis both leaving the game with leg injuries. Bourne was able to convert the extra looks into a two-yard touchdown for his second touchdown of the year. He will return to his backup role once Goodwin and Pettis return to action.
report: Kendrick Bourne caught 3-of-4 targets for 34 yards and a touchdown in the 49ers' Week 4 loss to the Chargers.

impact: Yeldon will play through his ankle injury and figures to carry the load Sunday with workhorse Leonard Fournette (hamstring) headed for another absence. Tennessee's run defense doesn't pose much of a threat as the Titans have yielded the seventh-most rushing yards per game this season. Yeldon is worth firing up as a borderline RB2 in all fantasy leagues this week.
report: T.J. Yeldon (questionable, ankle) is expected to play Week 3 against the Titans.

impact: The Jaguars started Corey Grant, but he managed 10 yards on seven touches and Yeldon showed the hotter hand.  In a game where Jacksonville's passing attack was almost entirely nonexistent, Yeldon led the team in receiving yards.  Leonard Fournette (hamstring) is tentatively due back for Week 4 against the Jets, which would render Yeldon and Grant useless as fantasy options.
report: T.J. Yeldon rushed seven times for 44 yards and caught 6-of-7 targets for 46 yards in the Jaguars' Week 3 loss to Tennessee.

impact: Yeldon replaced an injured Leonard Fournette in the second quarter.  He went untouched on a 31-yard screen for his first touchdown, and added a one-yard goal-line TD in mopup time. With Fournette dealing with a setback, Yeldon could be in line for another start this week. He'll be a plug-and-play RB2 if Fournette sits.
report: T.J. Yeldon had 18 carries for 52 yards and a touchdown and caught three passes for 48 yards and a receiving touchdown in Week 4 against the Jets.

impact: With Corey Grant exiting early, it was all Yeldon in this one. He looked great early in the game, consistently gaining big yardage on the ground. That stopped with the Jaguars down big in the second half, but he kept things going in the passing game. He caught Blake Bortles' only touchdown pass when he easily beat a linebacker on a wheel route from 14 yards out. With Leonard Fournette looking doubtful for Week 6, Yeldon will be a high-end RB2 against the Cowboys.
report: T.J. Yeldon rushed 10 times for 53 yards and hauled in 8-of-10 targets for 69 yards and a touchdown in the Jaguars' Week 5 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Yeldon never had a chance with Jacksonville playing from behind almost the entire game. With the Jags in catch-up mode, Yeldon saw just three carries in the second half. The 25-year-old has served as Jacksonville's workhorse during Leonard Fournette's absence. If Fournette (hamstring) can't get the green light in Week 7, Yeldon would draw another start against Houston.
report: T.J. Yeldon contributed just 41 yards on eight carries while turning five targets into three catches for 29 yards Sunday in Jacksonville’s Week 6 loss to the Cowboys.

impact: Yeldon operated as Jacksonville’s feature back for one last week; Carlos Hyde will likely take over as the Jags’ primary ball carrier in Week 8 against the Eagles in London. Yeldon should continue to dominate passing-game work until Leonard Fournette (hamstring) returns, but he has devolved from an every-week RB2 to a low-end flex option going forward.
report: T.J. Yeldon rushed 12 times for 28 yards and caught 5-of-7 targets for 40 yards and a touchdown in the Jaguars’ Week 7 loss to Houston.

impact: Perriman will make his Browns debut with Rishard Higgins (MCL) still sidelined. He'll be at best the No. 4 wideout behind Jarvis Landry, Antonio Callaway, and Damion Ratley. Inactive for Cleveland are QB Drew Stanton, WR Da’Mari Scott, CB E.J. Gaines, MLB Joe Schobert, and DL Carl Davis.
report: Breshad Perriman is active for Week 7 against the Bucs.

impact: Pro Football Focus charted Gates as playing 33-of-82 snaps. His production was identical to Virgil Green's. Gates will be on the TE2 radar for Week 2 against a Bills defense that struggled to defend the middle of the field last season.
report: Antonio Gates caught 2-of-3 passes for 16 yards in the Chargers' Week 1 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: He had just one target. Gates has been an afterthought in the Chargers' offense after two catches in the season opener. He's droppable in fantasy leagues.
report: Antonio Gates was held without a catch in Week 2 against Buffalo.

impact: Gates missed practice time this week due to an illness but he's going to gut it out on Sunday. The veteran has played limited snaps this year and is unlikely to be a factor against the Rams' elite secondary. The 38-year-old no longer carries any fantasy significance.
report: Antonio Gates (questionable, illness) is expected to play Week 3 against the Rams.

impact: The Chargers inactive list confirms Adam Schefter's report that Gates is available to play against the Rams. The Chargers, however, will be without WR Travis Benjamin (foot), LB Emmanuel Ellerbee, C Cole Toner, RT Joe Barksdale, G Forrest Lamp, DT T.Y. McGill, and DE Joey Bosa, who is expected to miss multiple weeks.
report: Antonio Gates (illness) is officially active for Week 3 against the Rams.

impact: The five targets are a season-high for the veteran tight end. Gates' red zone ability could lead him to a few touchdowns this year, but the 38-year-old is off the fantasy radar with how little volume he has seen.
report: Antonio Gates caught 3-of-5 targets for 45 yards in the Chargers' Week 3 loss to the Rams.

impact: That's back-to-back games with five targets, but he was able to score a touchdown this time around when he escaped to the corner of the end zone without a defender in sight. Gates is a touchdown-dependent TE2, but there should be a couple touchdown opportunities next week against the Raiders.
report: Antonio Gates caught 2-of-5 targets for 26 yards and a touchdown in the Chargers' Week 4 win over the 49ers.

impact: Gates remains a touchdown-dependent streamer as he's posted just 7-90-1 in the Chargers' last three games. With his weekly snaps continuously getting eaten into by fellow tight end Virgil Green (1-13-1), Gates can stay on the wire until the utmost perfect matchup presents itself.
report: Antonio Gates caught both of his targets for 19 yards in the Chargers' Week 5 win over the Raiders.

impact: St. Brown made the start as the No. 3 wideout with Randall Cobb and Geronimo Allison out.  He made a sliding 17-yard grab for his first NFL catch and had a late 54-yard pickup to pad the stats.  St. Brown will head back to the bench when Cobb and/or Allison come back, maybe as soon as Week 6.
report: Equanimeous St. Brown caught 3-of-5 targets for 89 yards in the Packers' Week 5 loss to the Lions.

impact: Callaway replaces Josh Gordon opposite Jarvis Landry. The Browns surprisingly gave Rashard Higgins more snaps than Callaway in Week 1, but with Gordon gone, Callaway will take over in two-wide sets. Callaway has a tough matchup against Marshon Lattimore this week, but his season outlook is on the rise.
report: Antonio Callaway is starting Week 2 against the Saints.

impact: Starting for Josh Gordon, Callaway failed to draw a target in the first half Sunday, but made his presence felt in the second half when he had catches of 18, 47 and 16 yards. The highlight of his day was reeling in a 47-yard vertical shot on 4th down to tie the game late in the 4th quarter. Callaway will provide uneven production moving forward as a secondary option in the Cleveland passing game, but his season is trending upwards with the Browns moving on from Josh Gordon and should be looked at in deeper leagues. The Browns will host the Jets on Thursday Night in Week 3.
report: Antonio Callaway caught 3-of-4 targets for 81 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 2 loss to the Saints.

impact: Callaway should have had a much bigger night, but Tyrod Taylor missed him on a gimme 75-yard touchdown in the first half. He also committed a few drops and quit on a route that might have resulted in a catch. It was a decidedly mixed effort from the Browns' new starting wideout, but his easy speed was on prominent display. With Baker Mayfield taking over at quarterback, Callaway could quickly push for WR3 status in fantasy leagues.
report: Antonio Callaway caught 4-of-10 targets for 20 yards in the Browns' Week 3 win over the Jets.

impact: It was an eventful day at the office for Callaway, who committed several drops and nearly lost a fumble on a fourth-quarter punt return, but Cleveland recovered.  Callaway nearly hit pay dirt on a 51-yard reception, only to be tackled down at the one-yard line before Carlos Hyde punched it in.  The good news is Callaway has commanded nine and ten targets in the last two games; the bad news is he has only 74 scoreless yards to show for it.  Callaway will remain an exciting-if-volatile WR4/flex option in Week 5 against the Ravens, who are getting back suspended top CB Jimmy Smith.
report: Antonio Callaway caught 3-of-9 targets for 54 yards in the Browns' Week 4 loss to the Raiders.

impact: After a dreadful performance a week ago, Callaway once again struggled on Sunday, dropping a crucial pass. Callaway entered the week dealing with a knee issue and the coaching staff mentioned dialing back his workload, which they did after he received nine and 11 targets over the two games prior. Callaway now has four or fewer receptions in every game this season and is still only a bench stash at this stage of the season. The Browns host the Chargers in Week 6.
report: Antonio Callaway caught 3-of-5 targets for 22 yards in Sunday's Week 5 win over the Ravens.

impact: Callaway once again struggled with missed opportunities as he lost a potential 45-yard touchdown in the sun in the first quarter and then had another straight drop on a potential long-gainer in the second half. He did secure a two-point conversion after the Browns' lone touchdown on the day. Callaway will continue to be force-fed targets as Cleveland has limited healthy bodies available at the wide receiver position, but he has caught just 8-of-24 targets over the past three weeks for 85 yards. Callaway will be an all-or-nothing option against a giving Tampa Bay defense in Week 7.
report: Antonio Callaway caught 2-of-10 targets for nine yards in Sunday's Week 6 loss to the Chargers.

impact: The two targets were the fewest that Callaway has received in a game since Week 1. He now has three or fewer receptions in every game on the season but one. Callaway has now reeled in just 9-of-23 targets for 99 yards over Baker Mayfield's four starts. Callaway is not a fantasy option heading into Week 8 against the Steelers.
report: Antonio Callaway caught 1-of-2 targets for 14 yards in Sunday's Week 7 loss to the Buccaneers.

impact: The sixth-round pick from Texas A&M was forced to step up into a large role in the Cleveland passing game with all of the injuries the Browns have sustained at the wide receiver position. His productive game came in game in which Jarvis Landry caught just two passes, so it should be taken with some degree of salt. That said, the Browns will still be without Rishard Higgins for a the short term and Antonio Callaway has proven to be an unreliable option. Ratley is only an option in the deepest of leagues, but the Browns face a terrible Tampa Bay defense on the road in Week 7 for those that must dig that deep.
report: Damion Ratley caught 6-of-8 targets for 82 yards in Sunday's Week 6 loss to the Chargers.

impact: After 15 targets in Week 1, we expected Landry to come to close to that number once again with the Browns shelving Josh Gordon, but that was not the case on Sunday. He still managed five receptions, the 19th consecutive game in which he's had at least five or more catches, the longest streak in the league. Landry will remain a strong WR2 asset Week 3 against the Jets.
report: Jarvis Landry caught 5-of-7 targets for 69 yards in Sunday's Week 2 loss to the Saints.

impact: Landry was limited all week in practice, but it always seemed like he was just getting some rest on a short week. Certain to get targets in a good matchup, Landry is a solid WR2.
report: ESPN's Dianna Russini reports Jarvis Landry (knee) is expected to play Thursday night against the Jets.

impact: Landry just needed some maintenance during the week. He will be his usual, highly-targeted WR2 self against the Jets. Inactive for the Browns are QB Drew Stanton, WR Rod Streater, LB Christian Kirksey, TE Seth DeValve, DL Emmanuel Ogbah, DL Ifeadi Odenigb and DL Devaroe Lawrence.
report: Jarvis Landry (knee) is active for Week 3 against the Jets.

impact: Landry committed a drop but was helping Baker Mayfield move the chains for the Browns' transformed offense after Tyrod Taylor (concussion) was forced from the game. Landry was the lone Brown getting his numbers while Taylor was under center, but his fantasy fortunes should improve with Mayfield taking over. Landry has a soft Week 4 matchup in the Raiders.
report: Jarvis Landry caught 8-of-15 targets for 103 yards in the Browns' Week 3 win over the Jets.

impact: Landry's ten targets led the team, but he was part of the problem in Cleveland's drop-pass fest and failed to get loose for any big plays.  Finishing with four catches snapped Landry's streak of catching five or more balls in 20 straight games.  Still, Landry has been targeted 18 times in roughly six quarters by Baker Mayfield, by far most on the team.  Keep rolling him out there in Week 5 against a Ravens defense struggling to slow slot receivers.
report: Jarvis Landry caught 4-of-10 targets for 34 yards and a touchdown in the Browns' Week 4 loss to Oakland.

impact: Landry was held in check by a Baltimore secondary. He had just one catch for 10 yards in the first half and needed receptions of 27 and 17 yards on the final three drives of the game to turn in a respectable line. Landry has had two 100-yard game surrounding three lackluster games, but is averaging a career-high 13.0 yards per catch with at double-digit targets in four of the first five games. He is strong WR2 in Week 6 against the Chargers.
report: Jarvis Landry caught 5-of-10 targets for 69 yards in Sunday's Week 5 win over the Ravens.

impact: Landry was stymied by the Chargers secondary all afternoon. His two receptions were the fewest he's had in a game since Week 14 of the 2015 season. Landry has struggled in the transition over to Baker Mayfield catching 11-of-29 targets for 114 yards over Mayfield's three starts. Despite those lowly numbers, Landry will be  in a spot to bounce back against a giving Tampa Bay secondary in Week 7.
report: Jarvis Landry caught 2-of-9 targets for 11 yards in Sunday's Week 6 loss to the Chargers.

impact: After just 11 catches for 114 yards over Baker Mayfield's first three starts, Landry had a season-high 10 catches on Sunday. Things started slowly as Landry had just four catches for 23 yards at the break, but then came on strong in the second half, securing 6-of-8 targets for 73 yards and a score. Landry found the end zone for the second time this season, a 16-yard score in which he made a diving catch and extended the ball over the goal line on his way to the ground to tie the game with 2:28 left in regulation. Landry has double-digit targets in every game this season and heads to Pittsburgh in Week 8 after already having a 100-yard game versus the Steelers in Week 1.
report: Jarvis Landry caught 10-of-15 targets for 97 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 7 loss to the Buccaneers.

impact: He's replacing Randall Cobb (hamstring) in three-wide sets. Cobb was playing 90 percent of snaps before going down, so Valdes-Scantling is going to get some serious run.  With Cobb potentially looking at a multi-game absence, Valdes-Scantling's dynasty stock is on the rise.
report: Marquez Valdes-Scantling will start in Week 4 against Buffalo.

impact: With Randall Cobb (hamstring) and Geronimo Allison (concussion) inactive, Valdes-Scantling and fellow rookie Equanimeous St. Brown got the starts next to Davante Adams. MVS scored a three-yard touchdown on the opening drive of the third quarter after the Packers were shut out in the first two frames, and he had a second touchdown called back as it was ruled he was down at the half-yard line. Lance Kendricks scored the next play.  Valdes-Scantling's 10 targets were third on the team behind Adams (12) and Jimmy Graham (11).  Allison will likely be back Week 6, but Cobb may have a multi-week injury.  Once both are back, MVS will be irrelevant in redraft leagues.
report: Marquez Valdes-Scantling caught 7-of-10 targets for 68 yards and one touchdown in the Packers' Week 5 loss to the Lions.

impact: Hyde added three yards on one catch. He ran just nine times for 26 yards in the first half before having a positive drive in the 3rd quarter where he carried four times for 30 yards a touchdown. The Browns offensive line appears to be a real problem for generating consistent yardage, but Hyde handled 22-of-30 Cleveland rushing attempts to open the season. Hyde will be an RB2 option next week on the road versus the Saints.
report: Browns RB Carlos Hyde rushed 22 times for 62 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 1 game versus the Steelers.

impact: Hyde added one catch for seven yards in the passing game. It was the second-consecutive game where Hyde struggled on the ground, but was bailed out by a 1-yard rushing score, this time following a pass interference in the end zone. Hyde has now rushed 38 times for 108 yards through two games. He will remain a fringe RB2 in Week 3 versus the Jets.
report: Carlos Hyde rushed 16 times for 43 yards and touchdown in Sunday's Week 2 loss to the Saints.

impact: Aka, Hyde is going to have a police escort to the stadium. Hyde's significant other was reportedly induced last night, so it has been a long day for the Browns' feature back. As any new parent can attest, the adrenaline should be enough to get him through the game against the Jets. We are not adjusting his Week 3 rank.
report: NFL Network's Omar Ruiz reports Carlos Hyde is awaiting the birth of his child on Thursday evening but is expected to make it to FirstEnergy Stadium just before kickoff.

impact: He added two receptions for five yards. No joke: Hyde then had to rush to the hospital for the birth of his child. Best wishes to the Hyde family. As for the game, nearly all of Hyde's damage, including both his scores, came after Baker Mayfield checked in for Tyrod Taylor (concussion). The Browns' offense looked reborn with Mayfield under center, complicating the defense's thinking and freeing up running lanes. Hyde took advantage with his trademark power running. Hyde will be an upside RB2 for a tasty Week 4 matchup with the Raiders.
report: Carlos Hyde rushed 23 times for 98 yards and two touchdowns in the Browns' Week 3 win over the Jets.

impact: He has at least 17 touches in all four games and 22 or more in three of them.  Hyde's touchdown came from a yard out following Antonio Callaway's 51-yard catch.  Hyde drew just one target, however, and Nick Chubb broke off 63- and 41-yard touchdown sprints, potentially earning the explosive rookie more work.  Until the Browns make a tangible playing-time adjustment in the backfield, however, Hyde will remain a high-volume RB2 play.  Cleveland hosts Baltimore next.
report: Carlos Hyde rushed 22 times for 82 yards and a touchdown in the Browns' Week 4 loss to the Raiders.

impact: Hyde found little to no room against a strong Baltimore defense. He had a 17-yard run early in the game but was still held to 3.7 yards per rush on the day. Hyde has been living off of touchdown production early in the season, but still has amassed 17 or more touches in every game this season. That kind of usage is nothing to scoff at, making Hyde a volume-based RB2 in a better matchup Week 6 at home against the Chargers.
report: Carlos Hyde rushed 17 times for 63 yards while catching 2-of-3 targets for 14 yards in Sunday's Week 5 win over the Ravens.

impact: Hyde has now failed to score in back-to-back games and it has exposed the low floor he carries weekly. Hyde has rushed for 4.0 yards per carry in just once game this season and has rushed 31 times for 97 yards over the past two weeks. His biggest obstacle for maintaining a fantasy floor is he has just six catches on the season and was not even targeted in the passing game on Sunday. Hyde will enter Week 7 as a touchdown-dependent RB2 option in Week 7 on the road in Tampa Bay.
report: Carlos Hyde rushed 14 times for 34 yards in Sunday's Week 6 loss to the Chargers.

impact: Making his 2018 debut after serving a four-game suspension to open the season, Ingram got the start and out-touched Alvin Kamara 18-9, adding two catches for 20 yards on three targets.  It was evident right from the get-go that coach Sean Payton wanted to get Ingram involved and keep him involved after sitting out the first four weeks.  It was also an opportunity for Kamara to get some extra rest heading into the bye.  Moving forward, we expect Kamara to be used much more than he was tonight, but there's obviously some serious concern here with all the weapons and mouths in the New Orleans offense.  Kamara is unlikely to match his 22.75 touches per game mark from Weeks 1-4.  He's going to need big plays to maintain elite RB1 status while Ingram is very much a mid-to-high RB2 the rest of the way.  The Saints get the Ravens on the road in Week 7.
report: Mark Ingram rushed 16 times for 53 yards and two touchdowns in the Saints' 43-19, Week 5 rout of the Redskins on Monday night.

impact: Ingram out-touched Kamara 18-9 in his Week 5 debut, but Kamara had a 19-14 upper hand in Baltimore. Ingram received carries from the Ravens' six- and five-yard line but could not cash either in. Kamara found the end zone from two yards out in the fourth quarter. This is more how we were expecting the Saints' backfield to look following Ingram's return but nothing is settled after only two games. Ingram will be a touchdown-dependent RB2 for Week 8 against the Vikings.
report: Mark Ingram rushed 12 times for 32 scoreless yards in the Saints' Week 7 win over the Ravens, adding two catches for 10 additional yards.

impact: It was not a good performance from Bortles, who struggled to move the ball without Leonard Fournette. Jacksonville had three long scoring drives in the first half including a touchdown drive after Fournette exited, but their longest play of the second half lasted just six plays. They punted seven times after the break. With Fournette looking questionable, Bortles will have to show more next week against the Patriots.
report: Blake Bortles completed 18-of-33 passes for 176 yards, a touchdown, and an interception in the Jaguars' Week 1 win over the Giants.

impact: The 377 yards passing were the third most of Bortles' career. Aside from a second half pick on a questionable but not egregious decision, Bortles was as poised as he's ever been. He "took what the defense was giving him," alternating some big throws down the field with lots of checkdowns to his playmakers. Dede Westbrook turned one such play into a 61-yard touchdown, while RB Corey Grant was eating up yards on short targets. Bortles did not take a single sack. He will look to stay hot against the Titans' soft defense in Week 3.
report: Blake Bortles completed 29-of-45 passes for 377 yards, four touchdowns and an interception in the Jaguars' 31-20, Week 2 win over the Patriots, adding five rushes for 25 additional yards.

impact: After shredding New England for 377 yards and four touchdowns in last week's win, Bortles got nothing going beyond checkdowns in Sunday's ugly 9-6 home-game loss.  Tennessee got to Bortles three times for sacks, but his throws to the outside were too often off the mark, and the Leonard Fournette-less running game was nearly nonexistent.  Fournette figures to return from his hamstring injury for Week 4 versus the Jets.  Bortles will continue to be a high-variance QB2.
report: Blake Bortles went 20-of-33 passing for 158 yards and rushed five times for 27 yards in the Jaguars' Week 3 loss to the Titans.

impact: Bortles was sharp in this one, completing 15 of his first 16 passes. He put good touch on a 67-yard touchdown to Donte Moncrief, with his other TD a screen to T.J. Yeldon. Bortles has started to heat up with 300-plus yards and multiple touchdowns in two of his last three weeks. He has a streamable Week 5 matchup with the Chiefs.
report: Blake Bortles completed 29-of-38 passes for 388 yards with two touchdowns and an interception in Week 4 against the Jets.

impact: Bortles had a first half to forget. Despite some good throws down the field including a 36-yard pass to D.J. Chark, the early part of his game was marred by turnovers. He lost a fumble the play after the defense picked off Patrick Mahomes, had a horrific pick-six on an attempted screen pass the next drive, and threw an end-zone interception off his lineman's helmet. He made several great throws on a touchdown drive in the third quarter, but he came back with a bad interception overthrown to a double-covered tight end on the next drive. He added another meaningless interception at the end of the game. On the bright side, he threw for 430 yards and added a long rushing score deep in garbage time to pad his fantasy stats. Always a threat for a big game when Leonard Fournette is sidelined, Bortles will be on the streaming map next week in Dallas.
report: Blake Bortles completed 33-of-61 passes for 430 yards, a touchdown, and four interceptions in the Jaguars' Week 5 loss to the Chiefs, adding four carries for 34 yards and a touchdown.

impact: He took three sacks for a loss of 10 yards. Bortles threw for just 35 yards in the first half, which may explain why the Jags went into halftime with a 24-point deficit. Even with the benefit of garbage time, Bortles never got anything going, struggling all day against an underrated Cowboys defense. His lone touchdown came on a 34-yard bomb to Dede Westbrook early in the third quarter. Bortles has thrown five interceptions over his last two outings with both resulting in losses. He'll try to do better next time out against Houston.
report: Blake Bortles completed 15-of-26 passes for 149 yards with one touchdown and one interception while adding 22 yards on four carries Sunday in the Jaguars’ Week 6 loss to Dallas.

impact: The Jaguars made a splash by acquiring Carlos Hyde from Cleveland on Friday but it doesn't sound like they're interested in bringing in a quarterback to compete with Blake Bortles. Nick Foles, Eli Manning and Tyrod Taylor have all been linked to Jacksonville at different points in time, though the Jaguars have yet to pursue any of those options. Bortles has fallen on hard times recently, throwing five interceptions with  just two touchdowns over his last two outings.
report: ESPN's Adam Schefter reports the Jaguars have no plans to acquire a quarterback at next week's trade deadline.

impact: Bortles failed to move the ball at all, completing just 6-of-12 passes for 61 yards with two lost fumbles that directly led to Texans touchdowns.  Put simply, it was time.  Bortles has been as erratic as ever this season, showing no signs of progression, taking too many sacks, and turning the ball over far too often.  Kessler is a weak-armed game manager, but he is a better option under center for the Jaguars at this point.
report: Losing 20-0, the Jaguars benched Blake Bortles for Cody Kessler in the second half of Sunday's Week 7 game against the Texans.

impact: He and teammate Aaron Rodgers (knee) will both be available for Sunday's divisional tilt at Lambeau. Adams shined with five catches for 88 yards and a touchdown in last week's opener but gets a much tougher draw this week going against Vikings All-Pro corner Xavier Rhodes. RotoPat has Adams as his No. 14 wide receiver for Week 2.
report: Davante Adams (questionable, shoulder) is expected to play Week 2 against the Vikings.

impact: He was always expected to play. The problem is he is less than 100 percent, Aaron Rodgers seems at risk for an in-game setback, and Xavier Rhodes is likely to shadow him most of the day. Adams needs to be downgraded a bit. Green Bay declared S Josh Jones (ankle), LB Oren Burks (shoulder), WR Equanimeous St. Brown, WR J'Mon Moore, S Raven Greene, CB Deante Burton, and OL Alex Light inactive for Week 2.
report: Davante Adams (shoulder) is active for Week 2 against the Vikings.

impact: Despite shadow coverage from Xavier Rhodes, Adams was able to consistently get open on Sunday. His touchdown came on a quick out in which he was able to cut back and beat a couple defenders to the goal line. Unfortunately, he dropped one of his targets, had a long catch called back on a spurious offensive pass interference call, and had a touchdown knocked out of his hands, but he still put together a solid fantasy day in one of his toughest matchups of the season. Assuming Aaron Rodgers’ knee continues to cooperate, Adams will be a solid WR1 next week in Washington.
report: Davante Adams hauled in 8-of-12 targets for 64 yards and a touchdown in the Packers' Week 2 tie with the Vikings.

impact: Adams also drew a 21-yard DPI. Adams has yet to have a 90-yard game this season — he's averaging 68 — but has scored all three times out. He's the preferred red zone weapon for the best quarterback in football. Adams will have a good shot at making it 4-of-4 on TDs in Week 4 against the Bills.
report: Davante Adams caught 7-of-9 targets for 52 yards and a touchdown in the Packers' Week 3 loss to the Redskins.

impact: Adams was dealing with Tre'Davious White but aside from not finding the end zone, he had his typical game. With 25 percent of the season in the books, Adams is on pace for 112/1,140/12. That's certainly within his range of outcomes. Adams will remain a back-end WR1 for Week 5 against the Lions.
report: Davante Adams caught 8-of-14 targets for 81 yards in the Packers' Week 4 win over the Bills.

impact: As expected.  Geronimo Allison (concussion) and Randall Cobb (hamstring) are both out, so it'll be Adams, Marquez Valdes-Scantling, and a combo of fellow rookies J'Mon Moore and Equanimeous St. Brown filling the void.  Adams, despite the balky calf, is a locked-in WR1 as a big-time target hog.
report: Davante Adams (calf) is active for Week 5 against the Lions.

impact: What calf injury?  Adams was a late addition to the injury report during the week but looked no worse for the wear as he chewed up chunk gains all day against Darius Slay and others.  The 12 targets led the team on a day Randall Cobb and Geronimo Allison were out and injured.  Adams seemed to be the only target Aaron Rodgers could trust fully on a day he attempted 52 passes.  Adams should work over Richard Sherman and the Niners next Monday night.
report: Davante Adams caught 9-of-12 targets for 140 yards and one touchdown in the Packers' 31-23, Week 5 loss to the Lions.

impact: Adams has been on a tear the past couple weeks with Randall Cobb and Geronimo Allison sidelined with injuries.  In the two games, Adams has reeled in 19-of-28 targets for 272 yards and three touchdowns against the Lions and Niners.  Things didn't really pop off for him until the second half when Adams scored a 16-yard touchdown to tie the game at 30-30 with 1:55 left.  He then made multiple catches on the final drive to get the Packers into field goal range for the win.  This all came after he caught a nine-yard TD in the first quarter.  Cobb and Allison should be back after the Week 7 bye, but Adams will remain an obvious WR1 the rest of the way.
report: Davante Adams caught 10-of-16 targets for 132 yards and two touchdowns in the Packers' come-from-behind 33-30, Week 6 win over the 49ers.

impact: Ajayi did not show any ill effects from his back injury in this one, running hard and consistently creating yards after contact. He did briefly leave the game with trainers in the fourth quarter, but he was back on the field after a couple plays. His health will remain a concern, but Ajayi will be an RB2 as long as he is healthy.
report: Jay Ajayi rushed 15 times for 70 yards and hauled in 3-of-4 targets for 11 yards in the Eagles' Week 4 loss to the Titans.

impact: Ajayi also lost a goal line fumble early in the third quarter as the Eagles were trying to get back into a 17-3 affair. To top it all off, he was announced as questionable with a knee injury, though he did remain in the game. Wendell Smallwood out-gained Ajayi 71-34 on the afternoon. Yet to see truly elite usage or eclipse 81 yards from scrimmage, Ajayi is settling in as a low-end RB2. His health will be worth monitoring for Week 6, as the Eagles are playing in the Thursday night game.
report: Jay Ajayi rushed eight times for 29 yards in the Eagles' Week 5 loss to the Vikings, adding a five-yard reception.

impact: Smallwood's usage increased because Jay Ajayi missed almost the entire first half and Darren Sproles (hamstring) was out.  Unfortunately, Smallwood lost a fumble and Ajayi returned.  Smallwood shouldn't have a Week 3 role versus the Colts.
report: Wendell Smallwood rushed seven times for 28 yards and caught his lone target for a gain of two in the Eagles' Week 2 loss to Tampa Bay.

impact: Smallwood drew the start and out-gained Corey Clement despite receiving just 13 touches. His 4-yard touchdown rush with 3:02 left in the 4th quarter put the Eagles up for good. If both Jay Ajayi and Darren Sproles remained sidelined in Week 4, Smallwood will be in the mix as a FLEX option next week against the Titans.
report: Wendell Smallwood rushed 10 times for 56 yards and a touchdown while catching 3-of-5 targets for 35 yards in Sunday's Week 4 win over the Colts.

impact: With both Corey Clement and Darren Sproles sidelined, Smallwood served as the No. 2 back behind Jay Ajayi. It was not always pretty -- he missed a blitz pickup in the two-minute drill -- but he was able to provide a couple nice runs. With Clement's and Sproles' availability up in the air, Smallwood is worth a look in deeper leagues.
report: Wendell Smallwood rushed five times for 39 yards and hauled in 3-of-5 targets for 15 yards in the Eagles' Week 4 loss to the Titans.

impact: Corey Clement (quad) was announced as active but ended up playing zero snaps. Smallwood drew Jay Ajayi to a playing time standstill and out-gained him 71-34. He did have a first half lowlight with a red zone drop. Smallwood has shown signs of life the past three weeks but is still an uninspiring FLEX option in PPR leagues. He's a bye week "if you must" play.
report: Wendell Smallwood rushed three times for 27 yards in the Eagles' Week 5 loss to the Vikings, adding three catches for 44 additional yards and a touchdown.

impact: Smallwood’s 11 touches led the Eagles’ backfield; Corey Clement logged 10 and Josh Adams 4. Smallwood had multiple big plays nullified by penalties, including a monster screen pass of 50-plus yards that came about partly because of RG Brandon Brooks’ holding flag. Entrenched in a three-man backfield, Smallwood will be a sub-par Week 8 flex option against the Jags.
report: Wendell Smallwood rushed nine times for 32 yards and caught 2-of-2 targets for five yards in the Eagles’ Week 7 loss to the Panthers.

impact: The 19 touches were the most Clement has had in a game over his first two seasons, but he was out-gained by Wendell Smallwood 91-to-75 on the afternoon while Smallwood was the back who got the short yardage rushing opportunity. Clement's Week 4 fantasy status is largely dependent on the availability of Jay Ajayi and Darren Sproles Week 4 against the Titans.
report: Corey Clement rushed 16 times for 56 yards while catching 3-of-4 targets for 19 yards in Sunday's Week 3 win over the Colts.

impact: Rosenblatt notes the Eagles have already played a game without Jay Ajayi this season, and Clement played 55 percent of the snaps while finishing with 16 carries. Wendell Smallwood played just 35 percent of the snaps on his way to 10 carries, but he did score a touchdown. Clement has been sidelined since that game, so it is possible Smallwood gets a little more work Thursday night. Even so, Clement is the better fantasy bet. Both are worth a look as an RB3/FLEX.
report: NJ Advance Media's Zack Rosenblatt expects Corey Clement to lead the Eagles' backfield Thursday night against the Giants.

impact: He finished second on the team in touches behind Wendell Smallwood’s 11, and Josh Adams mixed in for 4. Clement’s on-field play has been wildly inconsistent this year, and his usage isn’t much more bankable in a three-man backfield that could soon add Darren Sproles (hamstring) to the mix. Against the Jaguars in Week 8, Clement will be a low-end flex option.
report: Corey Clement rushed eight times for six yards and caught 2-of-2 targets for 16 yards in the Eagles’ Week 7 loss to the Panthers.

impact: Juszczyk was on the field for 68 of San Francisco's 98 offensive snaps. He showed well as a receiver, nabbing three catches for a team-leading 56 yards in the first half. This game was sort of a perfect storm for Juszczyk with Matt Breida (ankle) injured and the Niners playing from behind. Fullbacks have grown almost extinct in today's NFL but Juszczyk continues to play a prominent role both as a blocker and a pass-catcher. In fact, he may be the best receiving back the Niners have at the moment.
report: Kyle Juszczyk nabbed six catches for 75 yards on seven targets while adding one rush for 12 yards Sunday in San Francisco’s Week 5 loss to the Cardinals.

impact: Morris was cooking in the first half before stalling in the red zone when he had four carries from the five-yard line and in before losing a critical fumble on the fourth attempt at the two-yard line.  Morris looked to have a strong grip on ball-carrying duties before halftime, but with the Niners chasing in the second half, Matt Breida was the main back.  At the end of the day, Morris posted as 12-38 rushing line to Breida's 11-46 line while adding a five-yard catch.  Morris wasn't targeted in the pass game.  This figures to be a timeshare most weeks, though Morris should have chances for big workloads in games the Niners hold the lead.  The Lions come to town in Week 2.
report: Alfred Morris rushed 12 times for 38 yards in the 49ers' Week 1 loss to the Vikings.

impact: Morris held a slight edge in touches (16-14) but Matt Breida out-gained the veteran by a convincing margin. Not usually known for his pass-catching prowess, Alf logged his most receiving yards in a game since 2014. Morris took much better care of the ball this week after fumbling twice in last week’s opener. Averaging a mere 3.31 yards per carry through two games, the 29-year-old will just be an RB3 for next week’s game in KC.
report: Alfred Morris soaked up 48 yards on 14 carries while nabbing both of his targets for 32 yards Sunday in the 49ers’ Week 2 victory over the Lions.

impact: Morris only had four yards on three carries in the first half as the 49ers' offense was sabotaged by penalties, but he helped jump-start things in the second half with steady, consistent gains. He also confirmed his goal-line status with a three-yard score in the third quarter. Unfortunately, touchdowns might be more difficult to come by moving forward with Jimmy Garoppolo dealing with a potential ACL tear.
report: Alfred Morris rushed 14 times for 67 yards and a touchdown in the 49ers' Week 3 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Matt Breida (knee) is also expected to play. Added the injury report mid-week, there was some real concern Morris would sit out. He will apparently give it a go, however. A somewhat touchdown-reliant fantasy asset in an offense likely to scuffle without Jimmy Garoppolo, Morris is shaping up as a low-end FLEX option.
report: ESPN's Adam Schefter reports Alfred Morris (knee) is expected to play Week 4 against the Chargers.

impact: Morris was added to the injury report mid-week, but he's going to play through his knee injury. Morris will be a low-end FLEX option with C.J. Beathard starting at quarterback and Matt Breida (knee) active as well.
report: Alfred Morris (knee) is officially active for Week 4's game against the Chargers.

impact: Even though it didn't show up in the stat sheet, Morris was subbed in for Matt Breida on the goal line early in the game, but he failed to convert it for a touchdown. The Butler will need to convert his goal line opportunities if he's to have any fantasy value moving forward. Those opportunities could be few and far between with C.J. Beathard as the quarterback. Morris' fantasy owners are only hoping for a touchdown against the Cardinals next week.
report: Alfred Morris rushed four times for 14 scoreless yards in the 49ers' Week 4 loss to the Chargers.

impact: Morris took over as the lead ball-carrier after Matt Breida left with a sprained ankle. Alf didn't do anything particularly notable, though the five targets were surprising as the 29-year-old has never been much of a pass-catcher. Breida's ankle injury doesn't appear serious, though it could keep him from suiting up next week at Green Bay. Morris would be a volume-based RB2 if Breida can't get the green light.
report: Alfred Morris went for 61 yards on 18 carries while also securing three-of-five targets for 30 yards Sunday in the 49ers’ Week 5 loss to Arizona.

impact: Morris played one offensive snap.  When he did touch the ball, Morris had an eight-yard run called back on a hold.  He remained stationed on the sideline as the Niners went with a Matt Breida-Raheem Mostert tandem in the backfield.  And those two shredded the Green Bay defense, combining for 148 yards and a score on 26 carries.  Mostert led the way with 87 yards on 12 carries (7.25 YPC) and likely stole Morris' job in doing so.  The offense was just so much more explosive with speed guys Breida and Mostert rather than slug Morris slowing the unit down with his three yards and a cloud of dust.  Morris can be dropped in all formats.
report: Alfred Morris didn't touch the ball in the 49ers' Week 6 loss to the Packers on Monday night.

impact: Even with Raheem Mostert once again stacking big gains, Morris led the team with nine carries as Matt Breida struggled with his ankle injury. Mostert would seem to have earned an even bigger role moving forward, especially if Breida is forced to miss time, but it does not seem like Morris is going away. Even so, he is not a fantasy option right now.
report: Alfred Morris rushed nine times for 25 yards in the 49ers' Week 7 loss to the Rams.

impact: It would be surprising to see Breida on the field after he managed just one limited practice this week, but he has made a habit of playing through injuries so far this season. Alfred Morris' value would take a hit if Breida suits up.
report: NFL Network's Tom Pelissero reports Matt Breida (ankle) is "pushing to play" Monday night against the Packers.

impact: It's a bit of a shocking development.  Breida managed to squeeze in one limited practice this week after getting hurt in Week 5 with a sprained ankle.  The extra day of rest apparently did him some wonders.  We're curious how much Breida will actually play.  Neither he nor Alfred Morris is an attractive fantasy bet.
report: ESPN's Adam Schefter reports Matt Breida (ankle) is expected to play Monday night against the Packers.

impact: Breida was injured last week but made a quick recovery despite practicing on a limited basis just once this week.  He's impossible to trust in fantasy.
report: Matt Breida (ankle, shoulder) is active Week 6 against the Packers.

impact: As has become too common, Breida aggravated his ankle injury early in this game. He quickly came back after getting re-taped, but he limped off the field again during the two-minute touchdown drive at the end of the first half and did not touch the ball again. Perhaps the 49ers were just playing it safe in the blowout loss. Breida has a great matchup next week against the Cardinals, but his injury history will make him a risky play even if he is able to suit up.
report: Matt Breida rushed five times for 15 yards in the 49ers' Week 7 loss to the Rams.

impact: This marks Garoppolo's first career loss after opening 7-0 as a starter.  Garoppolo tried to lead a comeback with the Vikings up by 18 deep into the third quarter, but the red-zone offense left a lot to be desired Sunday.  Garoppolo missed a wide-open George Kittle on a would-be four-yard touchdown and earlier overshot Kittle on a deep ball after he beat Harrison Smith.  Garoppolo also had a possible 80-yard TD dropped by Kittle.  His touchdown was a beautiful 22-yard hookup with rookie Dante Pettis after Garoppolo spun out of a sack.  He missed too many throws in this one, however, though it was a very tough road date with one of the league's best defenses.  The Niners will host the Lions in their home opener next Sunday.  Garoppolo will be a back-end QB1.
report: Jimmy Garoppolo completed just 15-of-33 passes for 261 yards, one touchdown, and three interceptions in the 49ers' 24-16, Week 1 loss to the Vikings.

impact: Jimmy G also took six sacks for a loss of 50 yards. Garoppolo dialed up a sideline pass to a wide-open Kendrick Bourne for his first touchdown of the day early in the second quarter. He added to his touchdown tally with another score in the third quarter, this time connecting with tight end Garrett Celek for 11 yards. Garoppolo narrowly avoided disaster in the fourth as a Tracy Walker interception was negated by a holding call on Quandre Diggs. That interception would have set the Lions up with first-and-goal and a chance to take the lead with just over two minutes remaining. As his six sacks would attest to, Garoppolo often held on to the ball too long, though all in all, Sunday was a much better performance than his last one against the Vikings in Week 1. Now 8-1 as an NFL starting quarterback, Handsome Jimmy will head to KC next week for a shootout with Patrick Mahomes and the 2-0 Chiefs.
report: Jimmy Garoppolo completed 18-of-26 passes for 206 yards and two touchdowns while contributing four yards on three carries Sunday in the 49ers’ Week 2 win over the Lions.

impact: Garoppolo decided to stay in bounds at the end of a fourth-quarter run and ended up taking a big hit on the sideline. Trainers appeared to be examining his left leg -- not his head -- on the sidelines, and that leg was extended straight out in front of him on the cart. Garoppolo had an up-and-down game before exiting, but he led the 49ers back in the second half. He finished the day with 251 yards and two scores.
report: Jimmy Garoppolo was carted to the locker room with a knee injury late in the fourth quarter Week 3 against the Chiefs.

impact: Garoppolo took a big hit along the sidelines late in the fourth quarter of San Francisco's Week 3 loss. It originally seemed like he could be dealing with a concussion, but he ended up being carted to the locker room with his left leg extended straight in front of him. If it is actually an ACL, Garoppolo will be the second offensive star the 49ers lose to an ACL tear after Jerick McKinnon suffered the same injury in the preseason. Brutal.
report: 49ers coach Kyle Shanahan said the team is "fearing" an ACL tear for Jimmy Garoppolo.

impact: Kessler replaced Blake Bortles a little after halftime following Bortles’ second lost fumble. A weak-armed game manager, Kessler engineered just one touchdown drive. Kessler’s pick came on a dropped pass, which deflected to Texans S Tyrann Mathieu. Kessler will presumably get the Week 8 start against Philadelphia in London, although he won’t be more than a low-end two-quarterback-league play.
report: Cody Kessler completed 21-of-30 passes for 156 yards, one touchdown, and one interception in the Jaguars' Week 7 loss to the Texans.

impact: One of Williams' missed connections was a dropped 39-yard touchdown in the end zone. There was no one in Williams' area code and he simply put the ball on the ground. It was a bad moment in a game full of them for the Chargers' offense. Rotating with Travis Benjamin and Mike Williams behind Keenan Allen, Williams doesn't have much of a WR5 case right now.
report: Tyrell Williams caught 2-of-5 targets for eight yards and a touchdown in the Chargers' Week 1 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: It was a quiet game for Williams, though he improved on his eight yards for Week 1. Williams has been dealing with a groin injury, but looked fully healthy. The Chargers' deep threat remains off the fantasy radar.
report: Tyrell Williams caught three passes for 48 yards in Week 2 against Buffalo.

impact: Williams' grip as the Chargers No. 2 receiver is really loosening with Mike Williams taking a second-year leap. Mike Williams had as many touchdown grabs (2) today as Tyrell Williams had receptions. Tyrell Williams is just a deep threat for Rivers and is off the fantasy radar.
report: Tyrell Williams caught two passes for 22 yards in the Chargers' Week 3 loss to the Rams.

impact: Williams had more targets than Mike Williams in a game where Travis Benjamin (foot) left in the first quarter. Tyrell can bring in an occasional long touchdown for Rivers, but his weekly floor is really low since he's averaging just four targets per game. Williams will look for his first 50+ yard game next week against the burnable Raiders.
report: Tyrell Williams caught 3-of-5 targets for 48 scoreless yards in the Chargers' Week 4 win over the 49ers.

impact: None of his catches resulted in a touchdown, of course. It was the third time this season that Williams has seen just three targets, which now puts him at just 19 on the year. If searching for positives, it was his first 50-plus yard outing of the year and he did manage to finish second on the team in receiving yards. At this point, The Gazelle should only be owned in deeper leagues.
report: Tyrell Williams hauled in all three of his targets for 66 yards in the Chargers' Week 5 victory over the Raiders.

impact: Williams did all of his damage in the first half. His day got started on a two-play, 85-yard drive in which he caught a 40-yard pass over the top of the defense and then a 45-yard touchdown pass in which he took the ball from Damarious Randall on a simultaneous reception in the end zone. Williams then added a 29-yard touchdown strike with 51 seconds remaining in the first half to put the Chargers ahead 21-6 at the half. Williams entered Sunday with 192 yards and one touchdown, so he won't be an option next week when the Chargers head to London to face the Titans.
report: Tyrell Williams caught 3-of-4 targets for 118 yards and two touchdowns in Sunday's Week 6 win over the Browns.

impact: Williams roasted Logan Ryan for a 75-yard touchdown on the Chargers’ first play. He had a quiet second half with the Chargers losing the time-of-possesion battle. Williams is a one-trick deep threat, but he's had a high floor this season, with at least 40 yards or a touchdown in 6-of-7 games. Williams gets a matchup with Seattle in Week 9.
report: Tyrell Williams caught four passes for 118 yards and a touchdown in Week 7 against the Titans.

impact: Johnson was a clear ancillary option in the Browns offense behind Carlos Hyde. Johnson managed six targets, but converted just one for a reception. With Tyrod Taylor's rushing mentality, Johnson may find opportunity hard to come by after catching at least 50 passes in each of his first three seasons and is only a fringe FLEX option next week versus the Saints.
report: Browns RB Duke Johnson rushed five times for 17 yards and caught 1-of-6 targets for eight yards in Sunday's Week 1 game versus the Steelers.

impact: Johnson had his second disappointing game in a row to start the year as he managed just five touches, his fewest in a game since Week 1 of last season. Through two games, Johnson has totaled just 35 yards on just 11 touches. He's not even worth consideration in fantasy at this stage until his opportunity expands heading into a Week 3 matchup versus the Jets.
report: Duke Johnson rushed three times for three yards and caught two passes for seven yards in Sunday's Week 2 loss to the Saints.

impact: He has finished with six touches or fewer in each of Cleveland's first four games.  Johnson did convert a two-point conversion on run around the edge of Oakland's defense, but he also dropped a pass and was out-touched by Carlos Hyde 22 to 6.  Johnson is waiver-wire material outside of Dynasty leagues.
report: Duke Johnson rushed twice for 11 yards and caught 4-of-6 targets for 45 yards in the Browns' Week 4 loss to Oakland.

impact: Johnson was again was a non-factor in the offensive game plan for the Browns. After averaging 4.6 receptions a year ago, Johnson now has 10 receptions on the season through five games. He is not worth holding onto in fantasy formats outside of Dynasty leagues.
report: Duke Johnson rushed five times for 35 yards while catching one pass for seven yards in Sunday's Week 5 win over the Ravens.

impact: This was by far Johnson's best game of the season, adding three plays of over 20 yards on the day with the highlight being a 32-yard catch and run. Despite the big day in producing yardage, Johnson still only managed six touches, giving him six or fewer touches in every game this season. Johnson is a risky-FLEX play Week 7 against the Buccaneers with his current volume levels.
report: Duke Johnson rushed twice for 36 yards while catching 4-of-5 targets for 73 yards in Sunday's Week 6 loss to the Chargers.

impact: We wouldn't read much into this. Johnson is listed ahead of Chubb out of seniority but may not start depending on what formation the Browns open in. Chubb remains the favorite to lead Cleveland in Week 7 carries.
report: Duke Johnson is listed as the starter for Week 7 against the Bucs.

impact: With hopes that Johnson would gain usage after the trade of Carlos Hyde, things remained the same as always for Johnson as he was out-touched by rookie Nick Chubb 18-to-5. The touch total is especially discouraging as the Browns trailed the entire game. Johnson now has six or fewer touches in every game this season and is not a fantasy option until usage truly changes.
report: Duke Johnson rushed one time for -4 yards while catching all four of his targets for 23 yards in the Week 7 loss to the Buccaneers.

impact: Nearly all of Williams' production came with the Chargers in fourth quarter comeback mode. That was also after Tyrell Williams and Travis Benjamin burned the team with horrible drops. If nothing else, the Chargers are going to need Williams in the red zone. Today did nothing to change his status as an upside WR5 you can start in a pinch. Hopefully that pinch comes later in the season.
report: Mike Williams caught 5-of-6 targets for 81 yards in the Chargers' Week 1 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Williams stayed involved on offense after playing 54 percent of snaps in the season opener. His touchdown came on an opening drive red-zone strike from Philip Rivers, but he faded over the second half. With Travis Benjamin dealing with a foot injury, Williams should continue to see his role grow.
report: Mike Williams caught two passes for 27 yards and a touchdown Week 2 against Buffalo.

impact: Williams took advantage of Travis Benjamin's absence by securing two touchdown grabs. The first score came on a beautiful 42-yard diving catch in the end zone where he showed why the Chargers selected him with the No. 7 overall pick in 2017. Williams appears to be over his back issues that plagued him all last year and his role should continue to grow. Even if Benjamin returns next week, Williams has earned WR3/4 status with his performance today.
report: Mike Williams caught 4-of-7 targets for 81 yards and two touchdowns in the Chargers' Week 3 loss to the Rams.

impact: Williams came crashing down back to earth after a career-best game last week. He tied for the sixth-most targets on the team even with Travis Benjamin (foot) exiting the game early in the first quarter. The No. 7 overall pick will have his ups-and-downs, but the talent is there if he can put it all together. Williams has a golden matchup against the Raiders next week, but he is just an upside WR4 until his usage levels out.
report: Mike Williams caught 1-of-3 targets for 15 scoreless yards in the Chargers' Week 4 win over the 49ers.

impact: After flourishing through the first three weeks of the season, Williams has recorded just 4-60 and no touchdowns on seven targets in his last two games. There will be better days ahead, but Philip Rivers' touchdowns tosses have seemingly been spread out this year due to the added layer of Melvin Gordon's and Austin Ekeler's usage in the passing game. Williams will remain a WR3 in Week 6 versus the Browns.
report: Mike Williams caught 3-of-4 targets for 45 yards in the Chargers' Week 5 win over the Raiders.

impact: Williams added one rush for 10 yards Philip Rivers missed Williams wide open on his first two targets and then he was hardly involved afterwards. Despite having three touchdowns on the season, Williams is a clear ancillary option in the Charger passing attack. He has totaled five catches for 64 yards over the past three weeks on 11 targets. He is a touchdown-dependent WR4 next week versus the Titans.
report: Mike Williams caught 1-of-4 targets for four yards in Sunday's Week 6 win over the Browns.

impact: Williams scored his touchdown on the Chargers' first drive of the second half. He had two end-zone targets, but couldn't come up with either of them. Williams briefly exited after getting shaken up late in the fourth quarter but didn't miss any time. He'll have the Chargers' Week 8 bye to get healthy.
report: Mike Williams caught a 55-yard touchdown in Week 7 against the Titans.

impact: Taylor added 77 yards and a touchdown rushing on eight carries to make up for a nondescript passing performance in the heavy rain. His fantasy day is a reminder that even when Taylor is a lackluster passing option, he's still a high-floor fantasy option due to his rushing ability. Taylor will be a popular streaming option Week 2 against the Saints.
report: Browns QB Tyrod Taylor completed 15-of-40 passes for 197 yards with one touchdown and one interception in Sunday's Week 1 game versus the Steelers.

impact: Taylor added 26 yards rushing on four attempts. Taylor was largely nondescript for the majority of Sunday, but connected on a 47-yard bomb to Antonio Callaway that tied the game on 4th down with 1:16 left in the game. Taylor will still remain a high-floor streaming option Week 3 when the Browns host the Jets on Thursday.
report: Tyrod Taylor completed 22-of-30 passes for 246 yards with one touchdown and one interception in Sunday's Week 2 loss versus the Saints.

impact: It will be hard to do this one justice in a blurb, but Taylor's night went as poorly as possible even before he was evaluated for a head injury. With the Jets showing zero respect for his arm, they teed off on the box, making life miserable for Taylor as the crowd chanted for Baker Mayfield. Taylor was one for his first seven, and things never got better. He took three sacks, all three coming on first down. He missed Antonio Callaway on what should have been a wide-open 75-yard touchdown and committee intentional grounding in the end zone. It was painful to watch. Even if Taylor gets cleared, Mayfield will finish the game under center.
report: Tyrod Taylor completed 4-of-14 passes for 19 yards in the Browns' Week 3 game against the Jets before leaving with a potential concussion.

impact: It makes for a cruel end to an extremely ugly night. Especially with the Browns having 10 days to prepare for Week 4, they will go ahead and make the switch at quarterback. Baker Mayfield will start against the Raiders with Taylor backing him up. That's if he can clear the concussion protocol in time. Taylor was going to be benched regardless of his health. His play was that poor through his first 2.5 starts.
report: Tyrod Taylor has been diagnosed with a concussion and is week to week.

impact: Benjamin has sat the last two weeks as a game-time decision. He's made enough progress to play, but his snaps figure to be limited. Benjamin will be returning behind Mike Williams in three-wide sets.
report: Travis Benjamin (questionable, foot) is expected to play Week 4 against the 49ers.

impact: Benjamin lasted ten minutes before the training staff had to take another look at him. He had been testing his foot the last couple weeks in pregame warmups but wasn't able to see game action until today. Even if he's healthy, Benjamin has been passed up by Mike Williams.
report: Travis Benjamin (foot) is questionable to return in the Chargers' Week 4 game against the 49ers.

impact: Benjamin left the game just minutes after kickoff after hauling in his first target of the game. He slammed his helmet on the sideline in frustration, as he knew he re-injured his nagging foot injury. Benjamin can be safely dropped with his foot injury and Mike Williams working against him.
report: Travis Benjamin (foot) has been ruled for the remainder of the Chargers' Week 4 game against the 49ers.

impact: Benjamin will make his first appearance since Week 4. He's unlikely to have much of a role, but it's a hit to Mike Williams' playing time. The Chargers inactives are RB Melvin Gordon, K Caleb Sturgis, LB Kyzir White, C Cole Toner, OT Trent Scott, OG Forrest Lamp, and DE Joey Bosa.
report: Travis Benjamin (foot) is active for Week 7 against the Titans.

impact: Standard operating procedure for one of the league's truly elite wide receivers. Allen is so quick in and out of his breaks and spent much of the afternoon toying with the Chiefs' replacement-level defensive backs. For Week 2 he gets a Bills secondary that got ripped by the Ravens on Sunday.
report: Keenan Allen caught 8-of-11 targets for 108 yards and a touchdown in the Chargers' Week 1 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Allen led the Chargers in receiving in a spread-it-out game from Philip Rivers. The Chargers got up big early and didn't need to pass much in the second half, so Allen didn't get a ton of chances to exploit Buffalo's secondary. Allen is averaging seven catches and 88 yards through two games. He gets a matchup with the Rams in Week 3.
report: Keenan Allen caught 6-of-8 passes for 67 yards in the Chargers' Week 2 win over Buffalo.

impact: Allen was bottled up by the Rams defense despite Marcus Peters and Aqib Talib leaving the game early with injuries. Instead it was Mike Williams -- he also had seven targets -- who did the damage for the Chargers. Near the end of the game, Allen limped over to the sideline in some pain, but it appeared to not be very serious. Assuming the injury is minor, Allen will be a WR1/2 in a home matchup against the Garoppolo-less 49ers.
report: Keenan Allen caught 3-of-7 targets for 44 yards in the Chargers' Week 3 loss to the Rams.

impact: That means Keenan Allen (knee, tooth) and Travis Benjamin (foot) are officially active. The matchup for Allen is fantastic with Richard Sherman (calf) and S Jaquiski Tartt (shoulder) both inactive for the 49ers. Travis Benjamin's usage will be something to watch with Mike Williams breaking out for the Chargers. Joey Bosa (foot) is expected to be sidelined until the second half of the season.
report: Chargers declare LB Kyzir White, C Cole Toner, T Joe Barksdale, G Forrest Lamp, WR JJ Jones, DT T.Y. McGill, and DE Joey Bosa inactive for Week 4's game against the 49ers.

impact: Allen missed some practice time this week with knee and tooth soreness, but he was able to play through it. The 49ers were down two starting players in the secondary, but Allen was held in check in a game that featured Melvin Gordon. Allen is still on pace for a 96-1,128-4 season receiving line on 144 targets despite three straight average games. Look for Allen to return to low-end WR1 form against the Raiders next Sunday.
report: Keenan Allen caught 7-of-10 targets for 63 scoreless yards in the Chargers' Week 4 win over the 49ers.

impact: Allen has now seen at least seven targets in every game, and at least nine in three-of-five. Although he's recorded just one touchdown on the year, his massive volume (nine targets per game) will inevitably lead to more fireworks-style outings for owners in the near future. His red zone usage has admittedly taken a hit with Melvin Gordon so heavily involved out of the backfield this year, but Allen's weekly floor still makes him one of the safest plays going in fantasy. He's on pace for a usage-hog 102-1,190-3 season, and remains a safe WR1 in Week 6 against the Browns.
report: Keenan Allen vacuumed 8-of-9 targets for 90 yards in the Chargers' Week 5 rout over the Raiders.

impact: Allen got his day started off strong with two catches for 33 yards on the opening drive of the game. The Chargers took the air out of the ball in the second half, but his rushing performance made his day a respectable one as his four carries were a career-high. In fact, for his career, Allen had just three rushes for 11 yards entering Sunday's game. Allen hasn't been the WR1 fantasy owners drafted to begin the season, but got off to a slow statistical start a year ago before turning it on over the back half of the year. Allen will be a high-end WR2 option Week 7 when the Chargers face the Titans in London.
report: Keenan Allen caught 4-of-6 targets for 62 yards while rushing four times for 41 yards in Sunday's Week 6 win over the Browns.

impact: Allen didn't get a ton of volume with Philip Rivers only attempting 26 passes. He had an on-field outburst after not getting targeted in the end-zone late in the fourth quarter. Allen has hit his floor all year but has only one touchdown. He's due for some positive regression in the second half.
report: Keenan Allen caught five passes for 72 yards in the Chargers' Week 7 win over the Titans.

impact: Brees was sacked once for a seven-yard loss. Even though it came in a losing effort, the 39-year-old was absolutely brilliant, slinging touchdowns to Michael Thomas, Ted Ginn and Alvin Kamara in Sunday’s slugfest. Brees and Thomas were nearly unstoppable together, connecting 16 times for an incredible 180 yards. Neither defense showed up on Sunday as the two teams combined for an insane 1,004 yards of total offense. We’ll see what the future Hall of Famer does for an encore when he faces the Browns in Week 2.
